WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:08.381 --> 00:00:09.840
- Welcome everybody.

00:00:09.840 --> 00:00:11.430
I'm Janet Rich-Edwards.

00:00:11.430 --> 00:00:14.310
I am one of the two
science faculty advisers

00:00:14.310 --> 00:00:16.410
for the Radcliffe program.

00:00:16.410 --> 00:00:17.520
John is the other.

00:00:17.520 --> 00:00:19.320
I cover the life sciences.

00:00:19.320 --> 00:00:20.700
And I'm an epidemiologist.

00:00:20.700 --> 00:00:24.760
So for me to be able to have
this day is really a thrill.

00:00:24.760 --> 00:00:27.060
It also marks the
beginning of sort

00:00:27.060 --> 00:00:29.880
of a year of epidemiology
and epidemics

00:00:29.880 --> 00:00:32.229
work that we're going
to be focusing on.

00:00:32.229 --> 00:00:36.120
So epidemiology
we usually define

00:00:36.120 --> 00:00:42.360
as the study of the incidence,
prevalence, distribution,

00:00:42.360 --> 00:00:46.830
and control of disease
in a population.

00:00:46.830 --> 00:00:49.610
Now you contrast
that with medicine

00:00:49.610 --> 00:00:54.500
which is about detection,
prevention, and cure of disease

00:00:54.500 --> 00:00:56.490
in individuals.

00:00:56.490 --> 00:00:58.340
And so we consider
epidemiology to be

00:00:58.340 --> 00:01:03.350
the science, the investigative
branch of population health.

00:01:03.350 --> 00:01:07.960
And when we think about various
levels of biomedical research,

00:01:07.960 --> 00:01:08.870
you think of--

00:01:08.870 --> 00:01:12.260
generally, we talk about
three, maybe four levels.

00:01:12.260 --> 00:01:16.020
You talk about your basic
or pre-clinical science,

00:01:16.020 --> 00:01:20.390
which you think of as bench
research, usually experiments,

00:01:20.390 --> 00:01:24.927
usually with animals
or cells or cell lines.

00:01:24.927 --> 00:01:26.510
Then you think about
the level that we

00:01:26.510 --> 00:01:29.900
call clinical research,
which very often involves

00:01:29.900 --> 00:01:31.940
recruiting patients to a study.

00:01:31.940 --> 00:01:34.190
That study might be
observational in nature,

00:01:34.190 --> 00:01:37.070
watching the course of disease
in a group of patients,

00:01:37.070 --> 00:01:38.810
or it might be
experimental, think

00:01:38.810 --> 00:01:43.760
of randomized clinical trials
for drugs as clinical research.

00:01:43.760 --> 00:01:46.700
Then we get to the level
of population research,

00:01:46.700 --> 00:01:49.070
or epidemiology.

00:01:49.070 --> 00:01:53.180
And here we're usually talking
about very large collections

00:01:53.180 --> 00:01:57.710
of data about individuals
within a population.

00:01:57.710 --> 00:01:59.780
Sometimes we go out
and collect these data

00:01:59.780 --> 00:02:03.617
by forming what we call cohorts,
an observational cohort.

00:02:03.617 --> 00:02:06.200
So you may have heard of, say,
the Nurses' Health Study, which

00:02:06.200 --> 00:02:10.130
has been following 121,000
nurses with questionnaires

00:02:10.130 --> 00:02:13.280
every two years since 1976.

00:02:13.280 --> 00:02:16.544
Or you might be talking about
secondary data analysis.

00:02:16.544 --> 00:02:17.960
You might be
analyzing data that's

00:02:17.960 --> 00:02:20.600
collected for other purposes,
say vital statistics

00:02:20.600 --> 00:02:21.740
registries.

00:02:21.740 --> 00:02:24.510
You might, for
example, go to Norway

00:02:24.510 --> 00:02:28.310
where they've got fantastic
ability to link all the records

00:02:28.310 --> 00:02:31.760
through sort of a citizen ID.

00:02:31.760 --> 00:02:33.620
And you might be
able to, say, link

00:02:33.620 --> 00:02:37.370
a woman's records of her
births to the records

00:02:37.370 --> 00:02:39.500
of her hospitalization
or even mortality

00:02:39.500 --> 00:02:42.620
and make connections
statistically by using

00:02:42.620 --> 00:02:44.450
these secondary data sources.

00:02:44.450 --> 00:02:47.390
And there are many different
methods of epidemiology

00:02:47.390 --> 00:02:50.360
and you'll hear about
many of them today.

00:02:50.360 --> 00:02:53.240
One of the tricks
about epidemiology

00:02:53.240 --> 00:02:56.330
and the fact that it's
largely observational

00:02:56.330 --> 00:03:00.200
is that we very rarely
can perform experiments.

00:03:00.200 --> 00:03:02.900
And when you think about
what is the gold standard

00:03:02.900 --> 00:03:04.820
of biomedical
proof, you're really

00:03:04.820 --> 00:03:09.290
thinking about experiments or
randomized clinical trials,

00:03:09.290 --> 00:03:11.540
usually placebo
controlled, usually blinded

00:03:11.540 --> 00:03:13.410
to the investigator
and the participant

00:03:13.410 --> 00:03:15.170
and the clinicians involved.

00:03:15.170 --> 00:03:20.900
Epidemiology can rarely have
that kind of experiment.

00:03:20.900 --> 00:03:24.110
And so we're challenged
to take questions--

00:03:24.110 --> 00:03:27.430
to distinguish cause
from correlation.

00:03:27.430 --> 00:03:29.900
And to give you a
really basic paradigm--

00:03:29.900 --> 00:03:32.880
you know, if you think about--

00:03:32.880 --> 00:03:39.080
you could do a study looking
at causes of lung cancer.

00:03:39.080 --> 00:03:41.240
And you could go
out in a population

00:03:41.240 --> 00:03:43.610
and survey them about their
cigarette smoking habits

00:03:43.610 --> 00:03:46.550
and ask them about the matches,
whether they carry matches

00:03:46.550 --> 00:03:47.690
or not.

00:03:47.690 --> 00:03:51.890
And if you aren't really
careful about your inference,

00:03:51.890 --> 00:03:55.280
you might conclude that carrying
matches in your pocket causes

00:03:55.280 --> 00:03:57.110
lung cancer, right?

00:03:57.110 --> 00:03:59.480
Now, we all know
that's a correlation.

00:03:59.480 --> 00:04:02.990
Carrying matches is correlated
with smoking cigarettes, which

00:04:02.990 --> 00:04:05.600
is the actual cause
of lung cancer.

00:04:05.600 --> 00:04:09.470
That seems so patently obvious,
painfully obvious, if you will.

00:04:09.470 --> 00:04:13.700
But in epidemiology we're often
dealing with very closely woven

00:04:13.700 --> 00:04:18.589
together potential
causes of disease that

00:04:18.589 --> 00:04:22.850
will also be correlated
with non-causes of disease.

00:04:22.850 --> 00:04:26.420
And our challenge as scientists
is to tease this apart.

00:04:26.420 --> 00:04:28.880
Because where we
would all like to go

00:04:28.880 --> 00:04:33.950
is to translation where you
take the science of epidemiology

00:04:33.950 --> 00:04:37.490
and you translate that into
effective public policy,

00:04:37.490 --> 00:04:40.850
effective new possibly
clinical protocols.

00:04:40.850 --> 00:04:47.030
But you want it to be based on
a pretty reasonable inference

00:04:47.030 --> 00:04:48.440
of cause.

00:04:48.440 --> 00:04:50.902
And one of the reasons we chose
the four scientists you'll

00:04:50.902 --> 00:04:52.610
hear about today is
because a lot of them

00:04:52.610 --> 00:04:57.620
focus on how can we get
better at distinguishing cause

00:04:57.620 --> 00:04:58.600
from correlation.

00:04:58.600 --> 00:05:01.016
So I think you'll be hearing
quite a bit about that today.

00:05:03.700 --> 00:05:06.220
So the four young
scientists we have here

00:05:06.220 --> 00:05:08.440
I'm really thrilled about.

00:05:08.440 --> 00:05:12.190
And each of them will talk
for about a half an hour

00:05:12.190 --> 00:05:14.130
and we're going to
group them into two.

00:05:14.130 --> 00:05:18.100
The first two are
going to be more,

00:05:18.100 --> 00:05:21.550
what you might be familiar with,
focused on infectious disease

00:05:21.550 --> 00:05:25.030
epidemiology.

00:05:25.030 --> 00:05:27.940
Our roots as a field, when
you think the word epidemics,

00:05:27.940 --> 00:05:29.440
you think of
infectious disease, you

00:05:29.440 --> 00:05:33.670
think of cholera outbreaks in
London in the 19th century.

00:05:33.670 --> 00:05:35.140
We have since evolved.

00:05:35.140 --> 00:05:38.860
And epidemics has
now writ much larger.

00:05:38.860 --> 00:05:42.740
So we have, consider, we have
epidemics of heart disease.

00:05:42.740 --> 00:05:45.370
We certainly have
epidemics of obesity.

00:05:45.370 --> 00:05:47.870
We have epidemics
of mental health.

00:05:47.870 --> 00:05:49.990
And so the second
half of the day

00:05:49.990 --> 00:05:53.860
is focused on some of these
other noninfectious disease

00:05:53.860 --> 00:05:57.430
epidemics, and particularly
epidemics in mental health

00:05:57.430 --> 00:05:59.710
issues and how
they're distributed

00:05:59.710 --> 00:06:03.830
throughout the population in
terms of health disparities.

00:06:03.830 --> 00:06:05.380
So to kick you off--
so what we'll do

00:06:05.380 --> 00:06:08.740
is we'll have two speakers
speak back-to-back

00:06:08.740 --> 00:06:12.379
and then we'll do 20 minutes
of questions after that.

00:06:12.379 --> 00:06:14.170
And then give you guys
break and then we'll

00:06:14.170 --> 00:06:16.060
go to the second
half of the program.

00:06:16.060 --> 00:06:19.090
So I will introduce to you
our first two speakers.

00:06:19.090 --> 00:06:21.880
So Neal Goldstein is
an infectious disease

00:06:21.880 --> 00:06:26.440
epidemiologist at Christiana
Health Care in Newark,

00:06:26.440 --> 00:06:28.930
Delaware, and also hold
a faculty appointment

00:06:28.930 --> 00:06:30.910
at Drexel University.

00:06:30.910 --> 00:06:34.360
His specialty is using secondary
data sources, particularly

00:06:34.360 --> 00:06:36.310
medical records.

00:06:36.310 --> 00:06:38.150
And his research spans
several disciplines,

00:06:38.150 --> 00:06:41.230
including vaccine preventable
diseases, sexual minority

00:06:41.230 --> 00:06:44.170
health, pediatric infectious
disease, and women's health

00:06:44.170 --> 00:06:46.150
around pregnancy.

00:06:46.150 --> 00:06:48.130
Most recently, he's
focused on this issue

00:06:48.130 --> 00:06:50.210
of translational epidemiology.

00:06:50.210 --> 00:06:52.660
So how do we move from
knowledge generation

00:06:52.660 --> 00:06:55.190
to application and advocacy.

00:06:55.190 --> 00:06:59.230
And his talk today is
going to be about infection

00:06:59.230 --> 00:07:02.670
in hospitals, whether we can
be moving from a model that's

00:07:02.670 --> 00:07:06.930
based on the
likelihood of disease

00:07:06.930 --> 00:07:09.360
being a function of the
patient, the characteristics

00:07:09.360 --> 00:07:12.300
of the patient, to really
change that and look

00:07:12.300 --> 00:07:13.860
at functions of the system.

00:07:16.770 --> 00:07:19.070
Our second talk will
be Alana Brennan

00:07:19.070 --> 00:07:21.560
who is an instructor in the
Department of Global Health

00:07:21.560 --> 00:07:24.860
and in epidemiology
at Boston University.

00:07:24.860 --> 00:07:27.350
Her main focus is
to apply bio stats

00:07:27.350 --> 00:07:30.620
and epidemiological
observation to cohorts

00:07:30.620 --> 00:07:33.770
in sub-Saharan Africa,
particularly around HIV

00:07:33.770 --> 00:07:37.670
and antiretroviral therapies.

00:07:37.670 --> 00:07:40.670
In particular, her work has
been related to changing South

00:07:40.670 --> 00:07:43.370
African National
treatment guidelines,

00:07:43.370 --> 00:07:46.250
early versus deferred
pediatric anti--

00:07:46.250 --> 00:07:51.040
it's so hard to say--
antiretroviral treatment,

00:07:51.040 --> 00:07:53.390
and as well as the economic
outcomes of patients

00:07:53.390 --> 00:07:56.030
receiving that
kind of treatment.

00:07:56.030 --> 00:08:01.490
She also focuses on when a
clinical trial is not feasible,

00:08:01.490 --> 00:08:02.000
right?

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:05.360
Often for logistical or
often for ethical reasons.

00:08:05.360 --> 00:08:08.579
How can we do
quasi-experiments which

00:08:08.579 --> 00:08:10.370
are research designs
in which investigators

00:08:10.370 --> 00:08:14.720
study quasi-random variation
exposures that occur naturally.

00:08:14.720 --> 00:08:16.890
And she'll talk
a bit about that.

00:08:16.890 --> 00:08:19.640
So with that introduction,
Neal and Alana, actually,

00:08:19.640 --> 00:08:21.260
why don't you both come on up.

00:08:21.260 --> 00:08:23.328
And Neal, you can take it away.

00:08:23.328 --> 00:08:26.136
[APPLAUSE]

00:08:28.950 --> 00:08:31.170
- Thank you for that
very nice introduction.

00:08:31.170 --> 00:08:33.570
It's really an honor
to be here today.

00:08:33.570 --> 00:08:34.770
So I want to--

00:08:34.770 --> 00:08:36.809
before I get into
the talk itself,

00:08:36.809 --> 00:08:38.909
I just want to give a
little bit of background

00:08:38.909 --> 00:08:43.169
as to why I chose
this particular area.

00:08:43.169 --> 00:08:45.450
As was stated, I did my
training in infectious disease

00:08:45.450 --> 00:08:46.980
epidemiology.

00:08:46.980 --> 00:08:51.460
And when I got to doing my
post-doc at this hospital,

00:08:51.460 --> 00:08:52.995
it was a community hospital.

00:08:52.995 --> 00:08:55.620
It's a large community hospital,
but it still very much focused

00:08:55.620 --> 00:08:57.150
on patient care.

00:08:57.150 --> 00:08:59.100
So the research that
was ongoing there

00:08:59.100 --> 00:09:02.430
was all about what are the
characteristics of the patients

00:09:02.430 --> 00:09:05.850
and what leads them to become
infected with some disease.

00:09:05.850 --> 00:09:09.090
So I wanted to bring more
of my traditional training

00:09:09.090 --> 00:09:12.120
as an infectious
disease epidemiologist

00:09:12.120 --> 00:09:14.370
into the hospital environment.

00:09:14.370 --> 00:09:19.980
And specifically, I worked in
the neonatal intensive care

00:09:19.980 --> 00:09:20.730
unit.

00:09:20.730 --> 00:09:22.200
So I'm going to
tell you everything

00:09:22.200 --> 00:09:24.720
I know about neonatology.

00:09:24.720 --> 00:09:26.100
It's only in two slides, though.

00:09:26.100 --> 00:09:30.450
And to start we need to focus
on why do the patients get sick

00:09:30.450 --> 00:09:32.280
in the environment.

00:09:32.280 --> 00:09:34.650
Well, one way is we can just
look at the characteristics

00:09:34.650 --> 00:09:35.920
during pregnancy.

00:09:35.920 --> 00:09:39.420
So did the mother have some
kind of markers of inflammation

00:09:39.420 --> 00:09:42.090
like chorioamnionitis?

00:09:42.090 --> 00:09:45.120
Was she group b strep carrier?

00:09:45.120 --> 00:09:47.640
And then these can lead
to vertical transmission,

00:09:47.640 --> 00:09:49.772
so from mom to the baby.

00:09:49.772 --> 00:09:51.480
There's also, though,
the characteristics

00:09:51.480 --> 00:09:53.910
of the babies themselves,
in that maybe they

00:09:53.910 --> 00:09:55.734
were born pre-term.

00:09:55.734 --> 00:09:57.150
So this would mean
they would have

00:09:57.150 --> 00:10:01.090
an underdeveloped immune system,
underdeveloped skin system.

00:10:01.090 --> 00:10:04.150
So these are what I would
call these intrinsic factors.

00:10:04.150 --> 00:10:06.420
And these are
definitely correlates

00:10:06.420 --> 00:10:09.060
of infection, in that
if you are pre-term,

00:10:09.060 --> 00:10:11.700
if you had a mom
that had chorio you

00:10:11.700 --> 00:10:15.709
are likely to become
colonized and infected.

00:10:15.709 --> 00:10:17.250
So the questions I
wanted to ask were

00:10:17.250 --> 00:10:21.550
all about what are other factors
that can lead to infections.

00:10:21.550 --> 00:10:26.160
So you can-- certainly, it can
be caused by your care team,

00:10:26.160 --> 00:10:27.940
your health care workers.

00:10:27.940 --> 00:10:30.330
If they are colonized or
infected with some organism,

00:10:30.330 --> 00:10:32.424
they can very easily
pass it to you.

00:10:32.424 --> 00:10:33.840
It also may be a
function, though,

00:10:33.840 --> 00:10:36.390
of the environment
itself, or even

00:10:36.390 --> 00:10:39.870
what we call fomites, which are
just kind of inanimate objects

00:10:39.870 --> 00:10:42.540
that harbor organisms so this
could be a medical device

00:10:42.540 --> 00:10:47.590
or it could even be as
simple as your cell phone.

00:10:47.590 --> 00:10:49.420
So when you deal
with when you go

00:10:49.420 --> 00:10:52.630
through an epidemiology
program, especially when you're

00:10:52.630 --> 00:10:54.910
in a communicable
disease mode, you

00:10:54.910 --> 00:10:58.240
will talk about this notion
of the epidemiologic triad.

00:10:58.240 --> 00:11:01.780
The idea is that if you can
block one of these pathways,

00:11:01.780 --> 00:11:06.260
you can potentially stop
transmission of some organism.

00:11:06.260 --> 00:11:09.100
So it's funny that cholera
was mentioned already,

00:11:09.100 --> 00:11:11.470
because I'm going to use
cholera as the example here.

00:11:11.470 --> 00:11:13.900
The host would be
people, it would be us.

00:11:13.900 --> 00:11:16.390
The agent would be
the cholera bacteria.

00:11:16.390 --> 00:11:19.910
And then the environment could
be where the cholera resides.

00:11:19.910 --> 00:11:22.870
So the idea is that if we
can block these pathways,

00:11:22.870 --> 00:11:25.420
we can stop cholera
transmission.

00:11:25.420 --> 00:11:29.770
For example, between the cholera
bacteria itself and the host

00:11:29.770 --> 00:11:33.160
you can make the host immune by,
say, giving them vaccinations.

00:11:33.160 --> 00:11:35.200
You've blocked that
pathway you can also

00:11:35.200 --> 00:11:37.810
block the pathway between the
agent and the environment,

00:11:37.810 --> 00:11:40.330
say, by coordinating
the water supply.

00:11:40.330 --> 00:11:43.930
And lastly, you can block
the environment host

00:11:43.930 --> 00:11:47.170
pathway by, say, making
sure that people have access

00:11:47.170 --> 00:11:49.091
to clean, potable water.

00:11:49.091 --> 00:11:51.340
So we're blocking these
pathways and we're potentially

00:11:51.340 --> 00:11:55.120
stopping cholera from
infecting the host.

00:11:55.120 --> 00:11:58.380
There's also this notion of a
vector that kind of operates in

00:11:58.380 --> 00:12:00.580
between these three areas.

00:12:00.580 --> 00:12:05.080
The easiest example of that
would be Zika virus or malaria.

00:12:05.080 --> 00:12:06.721
The vector in this
case is a mosquito.

00:12:06.721 --> 00:12:08.470
And that it functions,
it operates kind of

00:12:08.470 --> 00:12:10.810
between all these pathways here.

00:12:10.810 --> 00:12:13.804
So as we then switch
from this classical,

00:12:13.804 --> 00:12:15.220
you know, you're
in school, you're

00:12:15.220 --> 00:12:17.590
getting trained in
epidemiology to now

00:12:17.590 --> 00:12:20.180
how can we apply
this at the hospital,

00:12:20.180 --> 00:12:22.060
we can start substituting
things on here.

00:12:22.060 --> 00:12:25.870
So the host where I worked
it became the neonate.

00:12:25.870 --> 00:12:28.990
The agent that I'll
talk about are really

00:12:28.990 --> 00:12:32.050
health-- mainly associated
with health care acquired

00:12:32.050 --> 00:12:32.720
infections.

00:12:32.720 --> 00:12:36.400
So I'm going to talk about
methicillin-resistant staph

00:12:36.400 --> 00:12:38.680
aureus, M-R-S-A or MRSA.

00:12:38.680 --> 00:12:41.500
Going to talk about
something called

00:12:41.500 --> 00:12:45.400
sepsis, which is a
bacteria in the blood.

00:12:45.400 --> 00:12:47.124
We'll talk about a
variety of organisms

00:12:47.124 --> 00:12:48.040
that can lead to that.

00:12:48.040 --> 00:12:50.380
But I'm also going to
talk about colonization

00:12:50.380 --> 00:12:54.100
of a few other organisms,
pseudomonas and klebsiella.

00:12:54.100 --> 00:12:55.600
So those are our pathogens.

00:12:55.600 --> 00:12:59.320
The environment now becomes the
neonatal intensive care unit.

00:12:59.320 --> 00:13:01.900
The intermediary or the
vector is the health care

00:13:01.900 --> 00:13:05.240
worker or visitor in that they
are within this environment

00:13:05.240 --> 00:13:07.120
and they will interact
with the babies

00:13:07.120 --> 00:13:12.710
as well as potentially
the pathogenic organisms.

00:13:12.710 --> 00:13:14.990
Three research
questions that we were

00:13:14.990 --> 00:13:19.350
looking at for this
particular group of analyzes.

00:13:19.350 --> 00:13:23.027
The first is looking outside of
what are the intrinsic factors,

00:13:23.027 --> 00:13:24.860
so what are the
characteristics of the baby,

00:13:24.860 --> 00:13:27.500
we wanted to start incorporating
these extrinsic factors.

00:13:27.500 --> 00:13:30.440
Like, how does occupancy
lead to a greater

00:13:30.440 --> 00:13:33.350
risk for becoming septic?

00:13:33.350 --> 00:13:35.610
And I'll get into what
that means in a few slides.

00:13:35.610 --> 00:13:37.880
But also, how does the
patient care network

00:13:37.880 --> 00:13:41.030
or who the providers
are interacting with,

00:13:41.030 --> 00:13:44.450
how does that influence
possible spread of MRSA.

00:13:44.450 --> 00:13:46.970
And lastly, if we
can identify maybe

00:13:46.970 --> 00:13:48.890
some of these
other factors, what

00:13:48.890 --> 00:13:50.840
is it about the
environment itself,

00:13:50.840 --> 00:13:53.450
what is it about the
NICU, the bed space,

00:13:53.450 --> 00:13:55.790
the location of
the patient, that

00:13:55.790 --> 00:13:59.320
may have some correlation to
becoming colonised or infected.

00:14:02.070 --> 00:14:02.980
And I just want to--

00:14:02.980 --> 00:14:06.040
I have one slide here that's
kind of my methods-y slide.

00:14:06.040 --> 00:14:08.280
Because I want to just give
you a sense for how we're

00:14:08.280 --> 00:14:10.530
able to do this type of study.

00:14:10.530 --> 00:14:12.690
It's not as if we
are prospectively

00:14:12.690 --> 00:14:17.040
recruiting parents to recruit
their children into this study.

00:14:17.040 --> 00:14:19.380
These data already
exist, which is really--

00:14:19.380 --> 00:14:20.940
that's kind of one
of my wheelhouses

00:14:20.940 --> 00:14:23.820
is I like doing secondary
analysis of data

00:14:23.820 --> 00:14:26.100
that's already in the
electronic medical record.

00:14:26.100 --> 00:14:27.870
I feel like we have
so much information

00:14:27.870 --> 00:14:29.610
that already exists
that was delivered

00:14:29.610 --> 00:14:33.330
during routine patient care, we
can mine that and then ask some

00:14:33.330 --> 00:14:35.290
of these interesting questions.

00:14:35.290 --> 00:14:37.990
So what we have in the
electronic medical record,

00:14:37.990 --> 00:14:41.670
it can be thought of as a
cohort of neonates in that they

00:14:41.670 --> 00:14:44.670
are admitted to the neonatal
intensive care unit,

00:14:44.670 --> 00:14:47.820
and while they're in the NICU
we know what happens to them.

00:14:47.820 --> 00:14:51.480
We can follow them through
time and see did they

00:14:51.480 --> 00:14:53.700
develop one of these
outcomes of interest

00:14:53.700 --> 00:14:55.740
or did they have some other--

00:14:55.740 --> 00:14:57.150
did they not have the outcome.

00:14:57.150 --> 00:14:59.754
And that would be were they
discharged from the unit,

00:14:59.754 --> 00:15:01.170
were they transfer
somewhere else,

00:15:01.170 --> 00:15:04.550
or did they expire while
they were in the unit.

00:15:04.550 --> 00:15:06.440
So these three research
questions, now, we'll

00:15:06.440 --> 00:15:07.820
go through them one at a time.

00:15:07.820 --> 00:15:11.910
I'm putting the epidemiologic
triad back up here on the slide

00:15:11.910 --> 00:15:14.690
so you can get a sense for
which are the pathways--

00:15:14.690 --> 00:15:16.520
and I'm not sure if
it shows up that well,

00:15:16.520 --> 00:15:18.440
but they're highlighted in red.

00:15:18.440 --> 00:15:22.500
So the intrinsic factors that
we would traditionally focus on

00:15:22.500 --> 00:15:24.500
are really what's happening
between the pathogen

00:15:24.500 --> 00:15:25.490
and the neonate.

00:15:25.490 --> 00:15:28.580
But this talk is all about
these extrinsic factors.

00:15:28.580 --> 00:15:30.410
So that's these other
pathways that we're

00:15:30.410 --> 00:15:33.090
beginning to look at.

00:15:33.090 --> 00:15:35.070
So the first question
that we're tackling

00:15:35.070 --> 00:15:37.650
is this notion of occupancy.

00:15:37.650 --> 00:15:39.630
And the reason that
this question came about

00:15:39.630 --> 00:15:42.990
is because it's
almost in some way

00:15:42.990 --> 00:15:47.100
an easy way to explain if
there's an outbreak of, say,

00:15:47.100 --> 00:15:48.930
MRSA in the unit we
could just be like,

00:15:48.930 --> 00:15:51.590
oh, it was really
crowded at that time.

00:15:51.590 --> 00:15:54.130
You know, maybe that's
why there's some breakdown

00:15:54.130 --> 00:15:57.030
in hygiene going on.

00:15:57.030 --> 00:15:58.750
Maybe that's what's
going on here.

00:15:58.750 --> 00:16:02.280
So we wanted to say, all
right, is it really related

00:16:02.280 --> 00:16:04.170
to occupancy and what
does one actually

00:16:04.170 --> 00:16:05.850
mean by occupancy,
because it can be

00:16:05.850 --> 00:16:08.140
defined a whole host of ways.

00:16:08.140 --> 00:16:10.500
For example, it could
just be the number

00:16:10.500 --> 00:16:12.840
of babies in the
unit at any one time,

00:16:12.840 --> 00:16:14.850
and this is what we
would call this census.

00:16:14.850 --> 00:16:17.520
Or could be something
to do with the demands

00:16:17.520 --> 00:16:19.380
on the staff in the unit.

00:16:19.380 --> 00:16:23.310
And a proxy for this would be
what's the overall acuity, say,

00:16:23.310 --> 00:16:26.390
what is the proportion of
pre-term babies in the NICU

00:16:26.390 --> 00:16:28.650
or what's the proportion
of very low birth weight

00:16:28.650 --> 00:16:30.120
babies in NICU.

00:16:30.120 --> 00:16:32.730
Or it could be a function of,
say, just staffing levels.

00:16:32.730 --> 00:16:35.670
What's the nurse
to patient ratio.

00:16:35.670 --> 00:16:37.500
And one thing I want
to emphasize with this

00:16:37.500 --> 00:16:40.980
is that it's not
occupancy itself

00:16:40.980 --> 00:16:46.070
that leads to these outcomes
of being infected or colonized,

00:16:46.070 --> 00:16:48.480
it's this notion of being
a proxy for something else.

00:16:48.480 --> 00:16:52.890
Because maybe it's a breakdown
in sterile technique to access

00:16:52.890 --> 00:16:55.890
lines that's happening
as a result of increased

00:16:55.890 --> 00:16:58.230
demands on the unit.

00:16:58.230 --> 00:17:01.410
Well, getting right into
the results for this one.

00:17:01.410 --> 00:17:02.810
We looked at two measures, here.

00:17:02.810 --> 00:17:04.560
We looked at the notion
of just the number

00:17:04.560 --> 00:17:08.369
of occupied beds or the census,
we looked at the acuity.

00:17:08.369 --> 00:17:11.970
And what we saw was that
there was a modest risk

00:17:11.970 --> 00:17:16.410
increase in late onset
sepsis that was statistically

00:17:16.410 --> 00:17:19.619
associated with acuity,
not so much for census.

00:17:19.619 --> 00:17:23.400
And although this is,
again, a very modest effect,

00:17:23.400 --> 00:17:25.170
the way that I initially
did this analysis

00:17:25.170 --> 00:17:28.890
was it's kind of like for
each percentage point increase

00:17:28.890 --> 00:17:30.390
in acuity in the unit--

00:17:30.390 --> 00:17:32.100
so what I would
stress for this one is

00:17:32.100 --> 00:17:35.130
that if we're looking at,
say, the proportion of very

00:17:35.130 --> 00:17:37.830
low birth weight babies and
we were comparing a unit that

00:17:37.830 --> 00:17:40.620
had like 10% very low birth
weight babies to a unit

00:17:40.620 --> 00:17:43.830
that had 40% very low birth
weight babies, now all

00:17:43.830 --> 00:17:48.680
of a sudden we're talking about
a 60% association of late onset

00:17:48.680 --> 00:17:49.180
sepsis.

00:17:49.180 --> 00:17:53.130
So it becomes a little bit
more important of a predictor.

00:17:53.130 --> 00:17:55.410
Conclusions from this question--

00:17:55.410 --> 00:17:58.710
we saw that in times
of high unit acuity,

00:17:58.710 --> 00:18:02.610
we may need some additional
infection control precautions.

00:18:02.610 --> 00:18:04.470
As well as if you're
doing this type of work

00:18:04.470 --> 00:18:06.886
where you're looking at health
care associated infections,

00:18:06.886 --> 00:18:10.590
it's probably a good idea to
have some measure of occupancy

00:18:10.590 --> 00:18:13.870
in your analysis.

00:18:13.870 --> 00:18:15.850
All right, so switching
to what I think

00:18:15.850 --> 00:18:17.590
are the more
interesting ones, here.

00:18:17.590 --> 00:18:19.060
The second research
question is how

00:18:19.060 --> 00:18:22.090
does the patient care
network of a NICU influence

00:18:22.090 --> 00:18:23.320
transmission of a MRSA.

00:18:23.320 --> 00:18:24.610
Again, the triad's up there.

00:18:24.610 --> 00:18:27.010
You can see highlighted
in red which

00:18:27.010 --> 00:18:30.210
pathways we're operating on.

00:18:30.210 --> 00:18:34.310
And the outcome I'm interested
for this study is MRSA.

00:18:34.310 --> 00:18:39.210
And MRSA is a not uncommon
health care associated

00:18:39.210 --> 00:18:41.700
infection and the
consequences are particularly

00:18:41.700 --> 00:18:45.270
dire in neonates
because about a third

00:18:45.270 --> 00:18:48.000
of the ones that become
colonized with MRSA

00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:50.590
will go on to develop
invasive infection.

00:18:50.590 --> 00:18:52.050
So it's important
pathogen for us

00:18:52.050 --> 00:18:54.880
to target in the
hospital environment.

00:18:54.880 --> 00:18:59.400
And what we know is that about
20% to 40% of a patient's flora

00:18:59.400 --> 00:19:01.410
are the result of
cross-contamination

00:19:01.410 --> 00:19:02.980
via the health worker.

00:19:02.980 --> 00:19:05.130
They're this vector,
they're this intermediary

00:19:05.130 --> 00:19:07.860
that's going between patients.

00:19:07.860 --> 00:19:10.680
And one of the main correlates
of this transmission

00:19:10.680 --> 00:19:12.420
is proper hand hygiene.

00:19:12.420 --> 00:19:14.700
In fact, hand
hygiene is in itself

00:19:14.700 --> 00:19:17.100
composed of a couple
of different things.

00:19:17.100 --> 00:19:19.480
There could be the
notion of compliance.

00:19:19.480 --> 00:19:23.470
So that just how
many of your staff

00:19:23.470 --> 00:19:28.650
are doing hand hygiene, whether
it's the gel hand sanitizer,

00:19:28.650 --> 00:19:30.810
whether it's using sinks.

00:19:30.810 --> 00:19:33.900
But then you also have this idea
that you could be compliant,

00:19:33.900 --> 00:19:35.500
but are you doing it correctly.

00:19:35.500 --> 00:19:37.260
And that's this
notion of efficacy.

00:19:37.260 --> 00:19:40.680
Because it's comprised
of these two things

00:19:40.680 --> 00:19:44.250
I don't think you could
ever get 100% effectiveness.

00:19:44.250 --> 00:19:47.910
Because even if everyone
in your unit is doing it,

00:19:47.910 --> 00:19:50.310
we don't know that they
are doing it correctly.

00:19:53.510 --> 00:19:55.450
So to do this kind
of work we wanted

00:19:55.450 --> 00:19:59.860
to know how's the notion of
which providers that interact

00:19:59.860 --> 00:20:02.710
with a baby connect
infants together

00:20:02.710 --> 00:20:05.080
and then how could
this, perhaps,

00:20:05.080 --> 00:20:07.549
influence the spread of MRSA.

00:20:07.549 --> 00:20:10.090
So we needed to ascertain what
I was calling the patient care

00:20:10.090 --> 00:20:10.960
network.

00:20:10.960 --> 00:20:15.250
The idea is that I can go into
the electronic health record

00:20:15.250 --> 00:20:19.990
and I can see which providers
interacted with which babies.

00:20:19.990 --> 00:20:23.350
And then I can begin to link
providers and babies together

00:20:23.350 --> 00:20:25.444
by saying they took
care of this baby

00:20:25.444 --> 00:20:26.860
and then they went
on to take care

00:20:26.860 --> 00:20:28.510
of this baby and this baby.

00:20:28.510 --> 00:20:31.730
So you can develop these
grafts and we'll see one

00:20:31.730 --> 00:20:32.590
in a few minutes.

00:20:32.590 --> 00:20:36.547
But you have this
network that forms.

00:20:36.547 --> 00:20:39.130
And it's akin to something you
may have heard something called

00:20:39.130 --> 00:20:41.230
a social network
analysis and it's

00:20:41.230 --> 00:20:43.000
all about your
social networks are

00:20:43.000 --> 00:20:44.690
and how that can spread ideas.

00:20:44.690 --> 00:20:46.820
It's a similar
sort of idea, here.

00:20:49.420 --> 00:20:51.130
To give you a sense,
though, for what

00:20:51.130 --> 00:20:53.710
the type of interactions
we're looking at in the health

00:20:53.710 --> 00:20:57.250
record, as you can imagine, when
you're in an ICU environment,

00:20:57.250 --> 00:20:59.200
that's the most
intensive care that you

00:20:59.200 --> 00:21:00.820
would have in the hospital.

00:21:00.820 --> 00:21:02.740
So there's all sorts
of interactions

00:21:02.740 --> 00:21:04.090
that are happening.

00:21:04.090 --> 00:21:05.950
Some of those
interactions are kind of

00:21:05.950 --> 00:21:08.320
meaningless for our work
here in that they're just

00:21:08.320 --> 00:21:10.370
patient documentation
sort of things,

00:21:10.370 --> 00:21:13.960
those really don't contain any
risk of spreading a disease.

00:21:13.960 --> 00:21:16.180
Other ones, though,
they are more meaningful

00:21:16.180 --> 00:21:20.860
in that they have the
propensity to spread MRSA here.

00:21:20.860 --> 00:21:23.860
So we ranked the ones
in the medical record

00:21:23.860 --> 00:21:25.960
and I thought that
it would really

00:21:25.960 --> 00:21:29.440
be the more invasive
procedures are the ones that we

00:21:29.440 --> 00:21:30.100
would see here.

00:21:30.100 --> 00:21:33.070
It would be the chest tube
placement, central line,

00:21:33.070 --> 00:21:34.010
that kind of stuff.

00:21:34.010 --> 00:21:36.100
But in fact, the
majority of interactions

00:21:36.100 --> 00:21:38.980
that we see in our NICU are
just really routine things

00:21:38.980 --> 00:21:42.490
like taking vital signs, since
this is a population of babies,

00:21:42.490 --> 00:21:44.200
doing like a stool assessment.

00:21:44.200 --> 00:21:46.210
Nevertheless, this
still has a propensity

00:21:46.210 --> 00:21:51.050
to spread an organism
from one baby to another.

00:21:51.050 --> 00:21:54.310
And so this picture up here
that looks like a bird's nest,

00:21:54.310 --> 00:21:58.790
this is actually our
NICU on a given day.

00:21:58.790 --> 00:22:02.710
So what you have is
each red dot is a baby.

00:22:02.710 --> 00:22:06.190
And then the black lines are
connections between babies

00:22:06.190 --> 00:22:09.520
by health care
providers in common.

00:22:09.520 --> 00:22:11.260
When I first saw
this, you know, it

00:22:11.260 --> 00:22:14.590
suggests that, man, there
really is a lot going

00:22:14.590 --> 00:22:16.600
on a given day in the unit.

00:22:16.600 --> 00:22:20.470
But each one of these lines is
a potential for hand hygiene

00:22:20.470 --> 00:22:23.200
to break down, whether
it's not being compliant

00:22:23.200 --> 00:22:27.290
or it's not efficacious because
it wasn't done correctly.

00:22:27.290 --> 00:22:29.890
So we conducted this
simulation study here

00:22:29.890 --> 00:22:34.660
to model what this NICU network
looks like over a typical nine

00:22:34.660 --> 00:22:35.600
day admission.

00:22:35.600 --> 00:22:38.890
That that's the median
length of stay in our NICU.

00:22:38.890 --> 00:22:43.160
So I'm going to switch over,
see if I can play a video.

00:22:43.160 --> 00:22:45.630
All right, so what
we're looking at here

00:22:45.630 --> 00:22:49.740
is each dot represents
a baby in the NICU.

00:22:49.740 --> 00:22:52.770
The blue dots are babies
that are susceptible to MRSA

00:22:52.770 --> 00:22:56.250
colonization, the red dots
are babies that are already

00:22:56.250 --> 00:22:58.860
colonized with MRSA.

00:22:58.860 --> 00:23:01.800
The lines that you're seeing
drawing and as they update,

00:23:01.800 --> 00:23:05.160
these are interactions
that providers are having

00:23:05.160 --> 00:23:07.260
that link babies together.

00:23:07.260 --> 00:23:08.620
It's updated every hour.

00:23:08.620 --> 00:23:11.230
So the idea is that you have
these one hour care bundles.

00:23:11.230 --> 00:23:13.710
I look at everything that's
happened with a given

00:23:13.710 --> 00:23:15.750
provider for one hour
and all the babies

00:23:15.750 --> 00:23:16.800
they've interacted with.

00:23:16.800 --> 00:23:19.480
And then I begin to connect
these babies together.

00:23:19.480 --> 00:23:21.780
So now we can do
this simulation model

00:23:21.780 --> 00:23:25.080
where we follow over
time these interactions.

00:23:25.080 --> 00:23:27.990
And what I do here
is I allow for there

00:23:27.990 --> 00:23:30.900
to be the possibility
of MRSA transmission

00:23:30.900 --> 00:23:35.260
that's considered on, say,
hand hygiene effectiveness

00:23:35.260 --> 00:23:39.360
or some characteristic
of the baby.

00:23:39.360 --> 00:23:42.030
I don't know if you noticed,
but we started with two red dots

00:23:42.030 --> 00:23:42.760
up there.

00:23:42.760 --> 00:23:45.420
That meant there were two
MRSA-colonized babies.

00:23:45.420 --> 00:23:51.570
And here we are 80 hours
or so into this NICU

00:23:51.570 --> 00:23:56.390
and we're already at four
colonized babies here.

00:23:56.390 --> 00:23:58.140
So if I let this go
through the whole way,

00:23:58.140 --> 00:24:01.140
you end up with about five
MRSA-colonized infants.

00:24:01.140 --> 00:24:04.740
So it clearly demonstrates that
there is a lot of opportunity

00:24:04.740 --> 00:24:07.000
for MRSA transmission to occur.

00:24:07.000 --> 00:24:09.510
So this suggests to us that
there's a lot of opportunities

00:24:09.510 --> 00:24:11.090
for MRSA transmission to occur.

00:24:11.090 --> 00:24:13.530
And now that we've had the
environment constructed

00:24:13.530 --> 00:24:15.420
where we can
mathematically model it,

00:24:15.420 --> 00:24:18.510
we can begin asking questions
such as when we vary

00:24:18.510 --> 00:24:21.700
the amount of MRSA that's in
the unit at any given time,

00:24:21.700 --> 00:24:23.520
how does that affect
the spread of it,

00:24:23.520 --> 00:24:26.500
we can vary the hand
hygiene compliance,

00:24:26.500 --> 00:24:29.490
we can very care
attributes of the baby.

00:24:29.490 --> 00:24:32.550
So we know that infants that are
born pre-term or infants whose

00:24:32.550 --> 00:24:36.000
trachea is intubated
require additional care.

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:38.100
And on the basis
of this, we came up

00:24:38.100 --> 00:24:40.950
with these graphs
here the y-axis

00:24:40.950 --> 00:24:43.230
we're looking at
the post-simulation,

00:24:43.230 --> 00:24:46.650
so that means after nine
days in our simulated NICU,

00:24:46.650 --> 00:24:49.980
we're looking at the prevalence
of MRSA colonization.

00:24:49.980 --> 00:24:51.480
And then the group
along the bottom,

00:24:51.480 --> 00:24:54.720
these four groups that I have
here, one two three four,

00:24:54.720 --> 00:24:58.260
this is just kind of seeding our
NICU with starting prevalence

00:24:58.260 --> 00:25:02.460
of MRSA, so this would be one
baby out of the total amount,

00:25:02.460 --> 00:25:06.300
or about 2% of the babies
have MRSA, and so on.

00:25:06.300 --> 00:25:09.450
The gray bars then
represent the varying amount

00:25:09.450 --> 00:25:11.730
of hand hygiene effectiveness.

00:25:11.730 --> 00:25:14.070
The two extremes, the
white bar and then

00:25:14.070 --> 00:25:17.620
the black bar, white bar would
be no hand hygiene at all.

00:25:17.620 --> 00:25:20.850
So this is just assuming
that no one follows any hand

00:25:20.850 --> 00:25:23.550
hygiene at all, it gives
us a usable comparison.

00:25:23.550 --> 00:25:26.700
The black bar represents 100%
where everyone's doing it

00:25:26.700 --> 00:25:28.600
and everyone's
doing it correctly.

00:25:28.600 --> 00:25:30.870
So we acknowledge
that reality exists

00:25:30.870 --> 00:25:33.060
somewhere in between here.

00:25:33.060 --> 00:25:35.250
When I first started
with this analysis

00:25:35.250 --> 00:25:39.810
I had a bet going
with our ID physician.

00:25:39.810 --> 00:25:41.907
I thought there would
be a plateauing effect.

00:25:41.907 --> 00:25:44.490
I really thought there would be
this point of no return, where

00:25:44.490 --> 00:25:46.350
we just didn't see
any improvement.

00:25:46.350 --> 00:25:48.240
And he said that,
no, I think you are

00:25:48.240 --> 00:25:49.560
going to see a linear trend.

00:25:49.560 --> 00:25:51.900
You're going to keep
getting bang for the buck.

00:25:51.900 --> 00:25:54.780
I think in some way, the
jury's still out on that one.

00:25:54.780 --> 00:25:56.530
I kind of see that--

00:25:56.530 --> 00:25:58.767
I agree with him that
there is this linear,

00:25:58.767 --> 00:26:00.600
you keep getting return
for your money here.

00:26:00.600 --> 00:26:02.550
But there does seem
to be a little bit

00:26:02.550 --> 00:26:05.490
of plateauing that occurs, in
my opinion, towards the bottom

00:26:05.490 --> 00:26:06.180
here.

00:26:06.180 --> 00:26:08.580
But if we focus just
on this one over here,

00:26:08.580 --> 00:26:12.330
on the one that has 2%
starting prevalence,

00:26:12.330 --> 00:26:14.370
I don't have the
numbers in front of me.

00:26:14.370 --> 00:26:18.150
I just wanted to talk about
the overall picture here.

00:26:18.150 --> 00:26:21.210
But the number-- after
you follow this NICU,

00:26:21.210 --> 00:26:25.500
at 2% prevalence, even
with 88% hand hygiene

00:26:25.500 --> 00:26:28.830
effectiveness, which I think
is kind of a theoretic maximum,

00:26:28.830 --> 00:26:31.080
that still suggests
that post simulation

00:26:31.080 --> 00:26:33.930
you have about two, and
in fact, a little bit more

00:26:33.930 --> 00:26:36.360
than two babies
colonized with MRSA.

00:26:36.360 --> 00:26:39.240
In my opinion, then, that really
suggests that hand hygiene

00:26:39.240 --> 00:26:40.200
alone is not enough.

00:26:40.200 --> 00:26:42.180
There's never a
good enough level

00:26:42.180 --> 00:26:45.940
of hand hygiene in the
hospital environment.

00:26:45.940 --> 00:26:48.870
So that's one of our conclusions
from this work is that there's

00:26:48.870 --> 00:26:50.400
no good enough level.

00:26:50.400 --> 00:26:53.520
And the conclusion
number two in some sense

00:26:53.520 --> 00:26:56.647
that may be a bit
obvious or intuitive.

00:26:56.647 --> 00:26:58.230
The greatest risk
of MRSA colonization

00:26:58.230 --> 00:27:00.210
was for those who have
the most contacts.

00:27:00.210 --> 00:27:02.210
The neat thing about this
work is we're actually

00:27:02.210 --> 00:27:04.976
able to quantify what that is.

00:27:04.976 --> 00:27:06.600
And then to point
number three on here,

00:27:06.600 --> 00:27:10.950
in times of a high number of
initially colonized babies

00:27:10.950 --> 00:27:14.520
with MRSA, it really
warrants other interventions

00:27:14.520 --> 00:27:15.450
in then NICU.

00:27:15.450 --> 00:27:17.420
And these would
be things like we

00:27:17.420 --> 00:27:19.380
have isolation
rooms in our NICU,

00:27:19.380 --> 00:27:21.330
so placing the babies
in the isolation rooms.

00:27:21.330 --> 00:27:24.240
This is also something
known as cohorting.

00:27:24.240 --> 00:27:27.420
Or when you have
multiple babies with MRSA

00:27:27.420 --> 00:27:30.740
we like to group them together
in a certain area of the NICU.

00:27:30.740 --> 00:27:32.280
It could also just
be things like,

00:27:32.280 --> 00:27:34.920
should we consider
decolonizing them,

00:27:34.920 --> 00:27:40.170
should we do universal gloving
in addition to hand hygiene.

00:27:40.170 --> 00:27:43.310
It's all food for thought
for our infection control

00:27:43.310 --> 00:27:45.380
department.

00:27:45.380 --> 00:27:48.350
So the final research
question here

00:27:48.350 --> 00:27:53.180
is, what are the characteristics
of the NICU itself?

00:27:53.180 --> 00:27:55.520
We know that occupancy
seems to matter,

00:27:55.520 --> 00:27:58.370
we know that hand
hygiene is important.

00:27:58.370 --> 00:28:00.740
But what is it about the
environment of the NICU that

00:28:00.740 --> 00:28:04.250
may lead babies to becoming
colonized and infected

00:28:04.250 --> 00:28:06.090
with various organisms?

00:28:06.090 --> 00:28:09.020
All right, so a brief
recap of where we've been.

00:28:09.020 --> 00:28:11.990
We saw-- and I just mentioned
this-- that acuity of the unit

00:28:11.990 --> 00:28:13.730
seemed to be an
important predictor.

00:28:13.730 --> 00:28:15.380
The amount of care
required seemed

00:28:15.380 --> 00:28:16.970
to be an important predictor.

00:28:16.970 --> 00:28:19.090
And that's a picture
of our NICU up there.

00:28:19.090 --> 00:28:23.370
So we want to know, what is
it about the NICU itself?

00:28:23.370 --> 00:28:27.080
In fact, this is nothing new.

00:28:27.080 --> 00:28:29.060
And I'm returning to
cholera because it's

00:28:29.060 --> 00:28:31.130
such an instructional example.

00:28:31.130 --> 00:28:34.610
How many people have
heard of John Snow?

00:28:34.610 --> 00:28:39.159
And not the Game of
Thrones Jon Snow, but the--

00:28:39.159 --> 00:28:41.200
All right, so it's about
half, maybe a little bit

00:28:41.200 --> 00:28:42.560
more than half.

00:28:42.560 --> 00:28:46.100
In some sense, he's
one of the originators

00:28:46.100 --> 00:28:48.134
of this field of epidemiology.

00:28:48.134 --> 00:28:49.550
And you have to
put yourself-- now

00:28:49.550 --> 00:28:51.260
for this picture
to make sense, you

00:28:51.260 --> 00:28:55.160
have to put yourself back
into mid 1800s London,

00:28:55.160 --> 00:28:56.900
there's a cholera outbreak.

00:28:56.900 --> 00:28:59.990
And what John Snow did that
was so innovative at the time,

00:28:59.990 --> 00:29:02.480
and, again, may seem kind
of obvious to us today,

00:29:02.480 --> 00:29:06.110
was he just put the
cases on a map of London.

00:29:06.110 --> 00:29:09.080
And those are these
dark rectangles up

00:29:09.080 --> 00:29:10.370
here, the black rectangles.

00:29:10.370 --> 00:29:14.060
So he's putting these
places on a map and notices

00:29:14.060 --> 00:29:16.310
that they really
appear to be centered

00:29:16.310 --> 00:29:20.180
around one of these wells
in London on Broad Street.

00:29:20.180 --> 00:29:23.000
And lo and behold, when
they turned off access,

00:29:23.000 --> 00:29:26.030
when they locked the well
so people can no longer draw

00:29:26.030 --> 00:29:29.420
their water from it, this
particular outbreak subsided.

00:29:29.420 --> 00:29:32.510
This is what we would call
today in the field spatial

00:29:32.510 --> 00:29:33.770
epidemiology.

00:29:33.770 --> 00:29:38.750
And also is something we
often say in the field,

00:29:38.750 --> 00:29:43.080
in public health in
particular, that place matters.

00:29:43.080 --> 00:29:47.550
So I wanted to know, does
place matter in our NICU?

00:29:47.550 --> 00:29:49.470
We're looking at a
bunch of outcomes now,

00:29:49.470 --> 00:29:51.060
we're looking at
MRSA but we're also

00:29:51.060 --> 00:29:54.450
looking at sepsis again,
as well as being colonized

00:29:54.450 --> 00:29:57.270
among those babies that
are being ventilated,

00:29:57.270 --> 00:29:59.310
are they colonized
with certain organisms

00:29:59.310 --> 00:30:01.802
that have the potential to
cause invasive infection.

00:30:01.802 --> 00:30:04.260
And we're going to consider a
few different characteristics

00:30:04.260 --> 00:30:05.830
of our unit.

00:30:05.830 --> 00:30:09.250
Our NICU is what's known
as an open pod design.

00:30:09.250 --> 00:30:12.120
So you have these pods
and within a given pod

00:30:12.120 --> 00:30:14.280
you can have up to three
babies, occasionally

00:30:14.280 --> 00:30:16.200
four babies that
share this space

00:30:16.200 --> 00:30:19.530
depending on the
demands of the baby.

00:30:19.530 --> 00:30:21.930
But some of the areas in
the NICU you can only fit--

00:30:21.930 --> 00:30:24.660
some of the pods you can
only get a single incubator

00:30:24.660 --> 00:30:26.094
in there, single bed.

00:30:26.094 --> 00:30:27.510
Other ones you can
get up to four.

00:30:27.510 --> 00:30:28.860
So does that seem to matter?

00:30:28.860 --> 00:30:32.050
If you're in an area with
there only being a single bed,

00:30:32.050 --> 00:30:36.240
are you less likely,
say, to become colonized?

00:30:36.240 --> 00:30:38.820
As well as-- we're
looking at historic data

00:30:38.820 --> 00:30:40.980
here from our electronic
medical record.

00:30:40.980 --> 00:30:44.730
So at one point in our unit
we had a leaking ceiling tile

00:30:44.730 --> 00:30:48.870
and it turned out that the
water supply was contaminated

00:30:48.870 --> 00:30:53.040
with pseudomonas and it was
leaking near one of the pods.

00:30:53.040 --> 00:30:55.410
So we said, well, can
we use this as a marker,

00:30:55.410 --> 00:30:57.960
then, to see did more
kids that were in the pod

00:30:57.960 --> 00:31:01.230
during this period of
time get pseudomonas.

00:31:01.230 --> 00:31:04.140
Also at one point, and this
was really bizarre to me,

00:31:04.140 --> 00:31:07.330
but this predated when
I was at Christiana.

00:31:07.330 --> 00:31:08.725
In one of the rooms--

00:31:08.725 --> 00:31:10.710
the NICU is divided up
in these three rooms.

00:31:10.710 --> 00:31:11.940
One of the rooms had carpet.

00:31:11.940 --> 00:31:16.170
It's like, why would you
guys have carpet in an ICU?

00:31:16.170 --> 00:31:18.660
Because you have environmental
services that comes through,

00:31:18.660 --> 00:31:20.380
right, and they're
vacuuming it and it's

00:31:20.380 --> 00:31:23.970
kicking up all sorts of dust
and particles and organisms,

00:31:23.970 --> 00:31:25.809
as well, into the environment.

00:31:25.809 --> 00:31:27.600
But we're able to look
at that back in time

00:31:27.600 --> 00:31:30.224
and say, all right, if you were
in the room when it had carpet,

00:31:30.224 --> 00:31:33.870
did that cause an increased risk
of colonization or infection?

00:31:33.870 --> 00:31:37.730
And, as well, we threw in a
couple of markers of fomites.

00:31:37.730 --> 00:31:39.750
There is equipment--
there's spaces

00:31:39.750 --> 00:31:43.770
in the NICU where you can
fit more equipment for babies

00:31:43.770 --> 00:31:45.940
that require more care.

00:31:45.940 --> 00:31:50.340
There's also refrigerators that
store breast milk and medicine

00:31:50.340 --> 00:31:51.687
sprinkled throughout the unit.

00:31:51.687 --> 00:31:53.520
And one of the
neonatologists was asking me,

00:31:53.520 --> 00:31:55.560
you know, that
she thought it was

00:31:55.560 --> 00:31:57.800
related to the refrigerators.

00:31:57.800 --> 00:31:59.790
She thought, I think
those refrigerators

00:31:59.790 --> 00:32:02.520
have a contaminated--

00:32:02.520 --> 00:32:04.110
some part of them
is contaminated.

00:32:04.110 --> 00:32:07.410
Can we somehow model to see
if being near a refrigerator

00:32:07.410 --> 00:32:10.470
leads to an increased
risk for infection?

00:32:10.470 --> 00:32:12.810
And one final thing I
wanted to consider here

00:32:12.810 --> 00:32:15.840
is that, since we're doing
this spatial analysis,

00:32:15.840 --> 00:32:24.450
say I'm in a pod and a baby in a
neighboring pod becomes septic.

00:32:24.450 --> 00:32:27.120
They have some
kind of bacteremia.

00:32:27.120 --> 00:32:29.830
Does that then
influence my risk?

00:32:29.830 --> 00:32:34.020
Does proximity to other babies
influence a given baby's risk?

00:32:37.510 --> 00:32:40.140
So to do this work
first thing we needed

00:32:40.140 --> 00:32:43.230
was a spatial
representation of our NICU.

00:32:43.230 --> 00:32:46.350
Now it's not like if I
was doing work in Boston,

00:32:46.350 --> 00:32:49.030
it's pretty easy to find
a map of Boston to them

00:32:49.030 --> 00:32:50.790
plot cases of whatever.

00:32:50.790 --> 00:32:52.807
But there wasn't
this map of the NICU

00:32:52.807 --> 00:32:54.390
so we had to create
a map of the NICU.

00:32:54.390 --> 00:32:55.515
This is what it looks like.

00:32:55.515 --> 00:32:57.030
It's a u-shaped NICU.

00:32:57.030 --> 00:32:59.880
And one of the easiest
things I can do

00:32:59.880 --> 00:33:02.177
is create what's known
as a choropleth map.

00:33:02.177 --> 00:33:03.760
And you see these
all the time, right?

00:33:03.760 --> 00:33:06.690
If you look at like diabetes,
obesity, heart disease

00:33:06.690 --> 00:33:08.940
in the US, you see
these colored maps.

00:33:08.940 --> 00:33:11.910
And so it's very nice to
get a quick qualitative

00:33:11.910 --> 00:33:14.110
sense as to what's going on.

00:33:14.110 --> 00:33:16.201
So I picked one of
our outcomes here.

00:33:16.201 --> 00:33:17.700
The way that you
would read this map

00:33:17.700 --> 00:33:20.850
is the darker the shade
of red, the more numbers

00:33:20.850 --> 00:33:24.840
of these outcomes that occurred
within one of these pods.

00:33:24.840 --> 00:33:25.597
So I want to do--

00:33:25.597 --> 00:33:27.180
this is the point
in the talk where it

00:33:27.180 --> 00:33:28.590
becomes a little interactive.

00:33:28.590 --> 00:33:29.880
I want to do a quick survey.

00:33:29.880 --> 00:33:31.900
There's two options here.

00:33:31.900 --> 00:33:34.510
One is that you think,
just by looking at this,

00:33:34.510 --> 00:33:36.420
it looks like it's
just randomness.

00:33:36.420 --> 00:33:38.340
The other option
is that you think

00:33:38.340 --> 00:33:40.530
there are patterns to
what's going on here.

00:33:40.530 --> 00:33:45.330
In other words, there's some
spatial correlation going on.

00:33:45.330 --> 00:33:47.220
All right, so show
of hands, then.

00:33:47.220 --> 00:33:49.800
Who thinks this is
just randomness?

00:33:49.800 --> 00:33:53.930
This is random noise, what
we're looking at up here.

00:33:53.930 --> 00:33:54.430
One take?

00:33:54.430 --> 00:33:56.054
All right, I've got
a couple of takers.

00:33:56.054 --> 00:33:57.160
Looks like two or three.

00:33:57.160 --> 00:33:58.960
And then raise your
hand if you think

00:33:58.960 --> 00:34:01.190
that there's clear spatial--

00:34:01.190 --> 00:34:04.790
like, there's patterns,
here, there's hot spots.

00:34:04.790 --> 00:34:07.430
So the majority think
there are patterns.

00:34:07.430 --> 00:34:09.770
I fell into the camp where
I, when I first saw this,

00:34:09.770 --> 00:34:11.909
was like, there's clearly
patterns going on.

00:34:11.909 --> 00:34:14.098
If you look at the
bottom area here,

00:34:14.098 --> 00:34:15.889
there's definitely
something going on here.

00:34:15.889 --> 00:34:18.840
There's definitely
something going on here.

00:34:18.840 --> 00:34:21.244
So we're going to return to
that question in a minute.

00:34:24.230 --> 00:34:26.070
For this final
research question,

00:34:26.070 --> 00:34:30.020
we had three sub questions
that we wanted to investigate.

00:34:30.020 --> 00:34:32.270
First, was it random
or are there patterns,

00:34:32.270 --> 00:34:33.710
are there hot spots?

00:34:33.710 --> 00:34:36.860
Second, what about the
environment itself?

00:34:36.860 --> 00:34:40.989
Does this explain our
infections and colonizations?

00:34:40.989 --> 00:34:44.210
As well as does, you know, if a
neighboring baby becomes sick,

00:34:44.210 --> 00:34:49.130
does that influence
my particular risk?

00:34:49.130 --> 00:34:53.199
So to the first question,
was the distribution random?

00:34:53.199 --> 00:34:55.659
We do some fancy
statistics and what

00:34:55.659 --> 00:34:59.050
we end up with is that for
two of our outcomes, MRSA

00:34:59.050 --> 00:35:03.070
and sepsis, there
were patterns to it.

00:35:03.070 --> 00:35:05.980
It wasn't just randomness.

00:35:05.980 --> 00:35:07.450
For the other two
of our outcomes,

00:35:07.450 --> 00:35:11.330
though, it statistically
appeared to be random.

00:35:11.330 --> 00:35:14.800
So I got bad news in that the
outcome we were looking at,

00:35:14.800 --> 00:35:18.490
which was klebsiella, in fact
was statistically random.

00:35:18.490 --> 00:35:21.160
So that just goes to
show you can't always--

00:35:21.160 --> 00:35:23.680
a qualitative
interpretation sometimes

00:35:23.680 --> 00:35:27.920
doesn't lead you down the road
to the correct conclusion.

00:35:27.920 --> 00:35:31.510
All right, now to the
environment itself.

00:35:31.510 --> 00:35:35.930
On an earlier slide I brought
up the list of factors

00:35:35.930 --> 00:35:36.680
that we looked at.

00:35:36.680 --> 00:35:40.490
So this was things like does
being in a refrigerator matter?

00:35:40.490 --> 00:35:44.470
Does being in what we call
the carpeted quiet room,

00:35:44.470 --> 00:35:45.642
did that matter?

00:35:45.642 --> 00:35:47.350
So we looked at all
these factors, right?

00:35:47.350 --> 00:35:49.120
And what we found
was that none of them

00:35:49.120 --> 00:35:53.200
really mattered all that
much, except for pseudomonas.

00:35:53.200 --> 00:35:55.780
So now we're dealing
with being colonized

00:35:55.780 --> 00:35:58.660
with this bacteria in
your endotracheal tube,

00:35:58.660 --> 00:36:02.440
this is among things
that were intubated.

00:36:02.440 --> 00:36:05.230
And we saw that for them,
being in an area that

00:36:05.230 --> 00:36:10.990
required more medical equipment
seemed to suggest like a nearly

00:36:10.990 --> 00:36:15.250
two-fold or two and a 1/2
forward increase odds of being

00:36:15.250 --> 00:36:17.170
colonized with this organism.

00:36:17.170 --> 00:36:18.910
So that was of interest.

00:36:18.910 --> 00:36:21.570
And these models that
we're doing right here,

00:36:21.570 --> 00:36:24.010
they're controlled for all
of these characteristics

00:36:24.010 --> 00:36:25.700
of the babies themselves.

00:36:25.700 --> 00:36:28.720
So we're accounting for the
fact that some of these babies

00:36:28.720 --> 00:36:32.710
are going to have been born very
pre-term, have very low birth

00:36:32.710 --> 00:36:36.130
weight, may have had a
central line present.

00:36:36.130 --> 00:36:38.470
As well as how long that
they're intubated for, right?

00:36:38.470 --> 00:36:41.011
Because it stands to reason that
the longer you're intubated,

00:36:41.011 --> 00:36:43.870
the more likely your
endotracheal tube will pick up

00:36:43.870 --> 00:36:47.770
some kind of bug, acknowledging
that all the tubes start out

00:36:47.770 --> 00:36:50.050
sterile.

00:36:50.050 --> 00:36:54.660
And finally this notion of, does
a neighbor influence your risk?

00:36:54.660 --> 00:36:57.970
Here, again, doing
some fancy statistics.

00:36:57.970 --> 00:37:03.520
But what we ultimately find
is that MRSA colonization

00:37:03.520 --> 00:37:07.180
appear to be the only one where
if there was a neighbor that

00:37:07.180 --> 00:37:11.170
was MRSA-colonized, that
I was at increased risk

00:37:11.170 --> 00:37:13.570
for perhaps being
MRSA-colonized.

00:37:13.570 --> 00:37:16.520
When I first saw this result
I got very excited by it.

00:37:16.520 --> 00:37:18.176
But then I thought that--

00:37:18.176 --> 00:37:20.800
well, this is actually probably
just returning something that's

00:37:20.800 --> 00:37:22.530
already existing in our unit.

00:37:22.530 --> 00:37:25.150
In that MRSA-colonized
babies are already

00:37:25.150 --> 00:37:27.484
being placed in
the isolation rooms

00:37:27.484 --> 00:37:28.900
and they're already
being cohorted

00:37:28.900 --> 00:37:31.570
to certain areas in the NICU,
so it's probably actually

00:37:31.570 --> 00:37:32.710
just returning that.

00:37:32.710 --> 00:37:34.420
It's just telling me
that, yeah, there's

00:37:34.420 --> 00:37:36.919
this spatial auto-correlation
but you're the one causing it.

00:37:36.919 --> 00:37:39.580
It's not that MRSA
is more communicable

00:37:39.580 --> 00:37:40.850
than other organisms.

00:37:40.850 --> 00:37:44.440
So something I thought was going
to be more interesting, maybe

00:37:44.440 --> 00:37:45.300
not.

00:37:45.300 --> 00:37:48.730
We still have to talk about that
with the infection prevention

00:37:48.730 --> 00:37:49.960
group.

00:37:49.960 --> 00:37:52.210
The conclusions, though,
from this final research

00:37:52.210 --> 00:37:53.570
question here.

00:37:53.570 --> 00:37:56.890
What we saw was that the
intrinsic baby-specific

00:37:56.890 --> 00:37:57.391
factors--

00:37:57.391 --> 00:37:59.181
so, again, these are
things like your birth

00:37:59.181 --> 00:38:01.450
weight, your gestation, did
you have a central line--

00:38:01.450 --> 00:38:05.470
those appear to explain
most of the outcomes.

00:38:05.470 --> 00:38:08.650
But we still see
statistical evidence

00:38:08.650 --> 00:38:11.500
that there's extrinsic
factors at play here.

00:38:11.500 --> 00:38:14.440
We identified maybe
a few of them.

00:38:14.440 --> 00:38:17.950
I still think there's
more to be done here,

00:38:17.950 --> 00:38:21.460
that there's more factors
we just haven't uncovered.

00:38:21.460 --> 00:38:23.140
Because with this
type of study, where

00:38:23.140 --> 00:38:25.210
you're working with data
that's already existing

00:38:25.210 --> 00:38:27.220
in the medical
record, you kind of

00:38:27.220 --> 00:38:30.610
can only test for
what you have data on.

00:38:30.610 --> 00:38:32.980
So if we were designing a
prospective study from this,

00:38:32.980 --> 00:38:35.290
we could really
investigate a lot more.

00:38:35.290 --> 00:38:36.940
Maybe there's other
factors out there

00:38:36.940 --> 00:38:39.550
we just haven't uncovered.

00:38:39.550 --> 00:38:41.740
But definitely with MRSA
colonization, you know,

00:38:41.740 --> 00:38:43.900
it warrants isolation
and cohorting given

00:38:43.900 --> 00:38:47.530
the potential for transmission.

00:38:47.530 --> 00:38:51.000
When I give this
talk at our hospital

00:38:51.000 --> 00:38:55.570
I like to conclude with, so
what should we do as the NICU?

00:38:55.570 --> 00:38:59.350
Like, what should our
infection prevention group do?

00:38:59.350 --> 00:39:01.720
But I'm guessing
that none of you

00:39:01.720 --> 00:39:04.265
are with the Christiana
Care NICU and if you are,

00:39:04.265 --> 00:39:06.640
see me in advance because
that's a tremendous coincidence

00:39:06.640 --> 00:39:08.060
that you're here right now.

00:39:08.060 --> 00:39:10.240
So I thought that
would be nice to end it

00:39:10.240 --> 00:39:14.290
with what can we do as potential
patients in the health care

00:39:14.290 --> 00:39:15.760
system?

00:39:15.760 --> 00:39:18.010
Really one of the
easiest things to do

00:39:18.010 --> 00:39:20.670
is the notion of
hand hygiene, right?

00:39:20.670 --> 00:39:22.990
It's making sure
that your providers

00:39:22.990 --> 00:39:25.450
have done hand hygiene when
you're seeing with them.

00:39:25.450 --> 00:39:28.024
You're not going to insult
them by they come into the room

00:39:28.024 --> 00:39:29.440
and you don't see
them scrub down,

00:39:29.440 --> 00:39:31.760
you're not going to
insult them by saying,

00:39:31.760 --> 00:39:35.050
can you please use a gel
sanitizer while you're here.

00:39:35.050 --> 00:39:36.910
As well as you should
do that yourself

00:39:36.910 --> 00:39:39.020
when you're in a
hospital environment.

00:39:39.020 --> 00:39:41.570
They're gross places to be
because there's organisms

00:39:41.570 --> 00:39:42.070
all over.

00:39:42.070 --> 00:39:45.520
No matter how vigilant
environmental services

00:39:45.520 --> 00:39:47.890
can be in the hospital,
there's still more organisms

00:39:47.890 --> 00:39:49.570
there than you
would just encounter

00:39:49.570 --> 00:39:50.761
walking around elsewhere.

00:39:50.761 --> 00:39:53.260
But that's another thing that
you can do in addition to hand

00:39:53.260 --> 00:39:57.340
hygiene, ensuring that your
staff have hand hygiene,

00:39:57.340 --> 00:39:59.680
they follow those
practices, making

00:39:59.680 --> 00:40:00.970
sure the environment is clean.

00:40:00.970 --> 00:40:02.650
Like, you should be
able to look around

00:40:02.650 --> 00:40:05.650
and it should be clean
where you are in there.

00:40:05.650 --> 00:40:07.570
If it's not clean,
talk to someone

00:40:07.570 --> 00:40:10.780
to get environmental
services in there to go ahead

00:40:10.780 --> 00:40:12.567
and clean the area.

00:40:12.567 --> 00:40:14.650
Well, there's other things
that we can do as well.

00:40:14.650 --> 00:40:18.700
Like ensuring that we prescribe
antibiotics correctly.

00:40:18.700 --> 00:40:21.430
Because kind of what are the
implications behind this work

00:40:21.430 --> 00:40:25.540
is that if you are
over-prescribing an antibiotic,

00:40:25.540 --> 00:40:28.240
you can develop what's
known as resistance to it.

00:40:28.240 --> 00:40:30.580
And particularly with
MRSA, right, that's

00:40:30.580 --> 00:40:32.350
already resistant
to the methicillin

00:40:32.350 --> 00:40:33.560
class of antibiotics.

00:40:33.560 --> 00:40:35.380
So we see that by
being more vigilant

00:40:35.380 --> 00:40:38.530
with antibiotic prescribing,
you can potentially

00:40:38.530 --> 00:40:41.770
reduce the burden
that's caused by these.

00:40:41.770 --> 00:40:44.830
So that would just
be, you know, if you

00:40:44.830 --> 00:40:46.330
feel like you have
the cold, there's

00:40:46.330 --> 00:40:47.740
no need for an
antibiotic, right?

00:40:47.740 --> 00:40:49.210
I think most people know that.

00:40:49.210 --> 00:40:53.610
But if you're a senior
provider and they give you

00:40:53.610 --> 00:40:55.840
prescription for an
antibiotic, know the reason

00:40:55.840 --> 00:40:57.970
why they're giving
that antibiotic,

00:40:57.970 --> 00:41:00.230
make sure that it's the
appropriate class for what

00:41:00.230 --> 00:41:00.730
you have.

00:41:00.730 --> 00:41:04.120
These are all good
questions that they would

00:41:04.120 --> 00:41:05.490
be happy to talk to you with.

00:41:08.090 --> 00:41:11.510
So in closing, clearly,
work of this magnitude,

00:41:11.510 --> 00:41:14.022
I couldn't do without
a whole host of people

00:41:14.022 --> 00:41:15.980
that are much smarter
than myself, many of them

00:41:15.980 --> 00:41:18.780
are listed on this
slide over here.

