to evaluate HIV care

00:42:17.850 --> 00:42:19.770
and treatment.

00:42:19.770 --> 00:42:23.220
And this is all
secondary data analyses.

00:42:23.220 --> 00:42:25.570
So the HIV epidemic--
many people are probably

00:42:25.570 --> 00:42:27.460
very familiar of what's
going on worldwide--

00:42:27.460 --> 00:42:30.500
but in case you're not, there's
roughly 37 million people

00:42:30.500 --> 00:42:32.350
who are HIV positive worldwide.

00:42:32.350 --> 00:42:35.530
And the vast majority of them
are in sub-Saharan Africa

00:42:35.530 --> 00:42:39.290
where there's 26 million
who are HIV positive.

00:42:39.290 --> 00:42:43.160
And just to give you an idea
of how treatment has rolled out

00:42:43.160 --> 00:42:45.110
in this setting,
treatment wasn't

00:42:45.110 --> 00:42:48.134
available in resource-limited
settings until about 2004.

00:42:48.134 --> 00:42:50.300
And this is based on a
directive by the World Health

00:42:50.300 --> 00:42:52.400
Organization and
guidelines that we're

00:42:52.400 --> 00:42:56.960
bringing antiretroviral therapy
into government sector clinics.

00:42:56.960 --> 00:42:59.841
And so in 2004 treatment
became available.

00:42:59.841 --> 00:43:02.090
And it was based on certain
eligibility and guidelines

00:43:02.090 --> 00:43:05.220
because of resource and
financial constraints.

00:43:05.220 --> 00:43:09.910
Over time, in 2010, as
better drugs became available

00:43:09.910 --> 00:43:11.800
and the eligibility
criteria changed,

00:43:11.800 --> 00:43:14.650
more people became
eligible for treatment.

00:43:14.650 --> 00:43:17.860
2013 there was another increase
in eligibility or expansion

00:43:17.860 --> 00:43:19.870
of eligibility criteria.

00:43:19.870 --> 00:43:22.730
And then currently we're at
what we call universal test

00:43:22.730 --> 00:43:24.070
and treat or treat all.

00:43:24.070 --> 00:43:26.560
And that means that
anybody who is HIV positive

00:43:26.560 --> 00:43:28.300
and comes into a
clinic, they are

00:43:28.300 --> 00:43:30.070
eligible for treatment that day.

00:43:30.070 --> 00:43:32.830
And this, even though the
policy was started in 2015,

00:43:32.830 --> 00:43:35.470
most countries didn't
roll it out until 2016.

00:43:35.470 --> 00:43:37.270
September of this last year.

00:43:37.270 --> 00:43:38.860
And universal test
and treat is what

00:43:38.860 --> 00:43:42.550
it is, as far as I understand,
what is protocol in high income

00:43:42.550 --> 00:43:46.002
countries since roughly 2004.

00:43:46.002 --> 00:43:48.210
And then what has happened
also over this time period

00:43:48.210 --> 00:43:51.390
is we've gone from this
huge pill burden of patients

00:43:51.390 --> 00:43:54.030
having to take two to
three handfuls of drugs

00:43:54.030 --> 00:43:55.780
twice a day, two,
three times a day,

00:43:55.780 --> 00:43:57.840
to what one is a fixed
dose combination.

00:43:57.840 --> 00:43:59.640
So it's one drug, twice a day.

00:43:59.640 --> 00:44:02.870
So it's actually improved
patient care substantially.

00:44:02.870 --> 00:44:05.130
And patients are--
this is easy to do.

00:44:05.130 --> 00:44:08.440
Easier to do, to adhere to.

00:44:08.440 --> 00:44:10.009
And this graph is
just showing where

00:44:10.009 --> 00:44:12.550
we're at in different regions
