00:44:12.550 --> 00:44:15.160
to antiretroviral therapy
coverage for those

00:44:15.160 --> 00:44:16.510
that are eligible for HIV.

00:44:16.510 --> 00:44:19.674
And I'm just highlighting here
in the red box southern Africa

00:44:19.674 --> 00:44:21.340
and eastern Africa
regions because those

00:44:21.340 --> 00:44:23.440
are the regions that the
data is from that I'll

00:44:23.440 --> 00:44:24.870
talk about today.

00:44:24.870 --> 00:44:29.080
And if we look at--
this is 2010 to 2015.

00:44:29.080 --> 00:44:31.150
And in 2010 in the
southern African and east

00:44:31.150 --> 00:44:33.100
African region, we
see that about 25%

00:44:33.100 --> 00:44:35.200
of people who are
eligible for treatment

00:44:35.200 --> 00:44:38.920
actually got treatment for HIV.

00:44:38.920 --> 00:44:42.274
We see a substantial increase
to 2015 where about 55%

00:44:42.274 --> 00:44:43.690
of the population
that is eligible

00:44:43.690 --> 00:44:46.360
is actually accessing
antiretroviral therapy.

00:44:46.360 --> 00:44:49.540
And although there's
still a large unmet need,

00:44:49.540 --> 00:44:50.790
this jump is massive.

00:44:50.790 --> 00:44:52.280
A massive undertaking.

00:44:52.280 --> 00:44:55.010
So although there is about
50%, roughly, at least

00:44:55.010 --> 00:44:58.140
in eastern and southern Africa,
that are in need of treatment,

00:44:58.140 --> 00:45:03.400
this is not a small feat
to get to this point.

00:45:03.400 --> 00:45:05.010
So briefly about
observational studies

00:45:05.010 --> 00:45:06.150
and experimental studies.

00:45:06.150 --> 00:45:08.260
And Janet had talked about this.

00:45:08.260 --> 00:45:10.590
Most of the work that
I do, until recently,

00:45:10.590 --> 00:45:13.800
is in the world of observational
analytical research.

00:45:13.800 --> 00:45:16.380
And so our typical
prospective cohort design

00:45:16.380 --> 00:45:18.710
is where you have a
population of people,

00:45:18.710 --> 00:45:21.060
you choose a
subsample, you classify

00:45:21.060 --> 00:45:23.090
them as exposed or unexposed.

00:45:23.090 --> 00:45:24.840
And then you follow
them forward over time

00:45:24.840 --> 00:45:28.560
to assess who develops disease
or your desired outcome.

00:45:28.560 --> 00:45:31.950
And then you compare the
risk or rates in the exposed

00:45:31.950 --> 00:45:35.580
to the unexposed to look at the
magnitude of an association.

00:45:35.580 --> 00:45:37.560
And as Janet had
mentioned, basically, we're

00:45:37.560 --> 00:45:40.410
only looking at what we
believe to be correlations

00:45:40.410 --> 00:45:43.590
or associations causality
is difficult to establish

00:45:43.590 --> 00:45:46.020
when you're in
observational research.

00:45:46.020 --> 00:45:49.260
Where we can do that is in
the experimental study design,

00:45:49.260 --> 00:45:51.160
specifically the
randomized clinical trial,

00:45:51.160 --> 00:45:52.650
which is our gold standard.

00:45:52.650 --> 00:45:56.340
So you have your population,
your underlying population,

00:45:56.340 --> 00:45:58.080
you choose a
subsample, and then you

00:45:58.080 --> 00:46:01.575
randomize that sample to either
received treatment or control.

00:46:01.575 --> 00:46:03.450
And then again, follow
them forward over time

00:46:03.450 --> 00:46:06.270
to assess your desired outcomes
and to compare the risk

00:46:06.270 --> 00:46:08.850
or rates amongst the
treated to the control

00:46:08.850 --> 00:46:11.710
to look at the
actual causal effect.

00:46:11.710 --> 00:46:14.520
So if you're randomisation-- the
key here is that randomisation.

00:46:14.520 --> 00:46:16.170
If you're
randomisation held, you

00:46:16.170 --> 00:46:19.180
can actually establish causality
in a randomized clinical trial,

00:46:19.180 --> 00:46:22.100
which is what we're
always trying to go for.

00:46:22.100 --> 00:46:25.550
So in my mentorship
for the last five years

00:46:25.550 --> 00:46:27.920
with Professor Matthew
Fox, he's always

00:46:27.920 --> 00:46:30.880
challenged us to
think about when

00:46:30.880 --> 00:46:32.780
we're working
observational research,

00:46:32.780 --> 00:46:35.900
how can we get as close
to a clinical trial

00:46:35.900 --> 00:46:39.225
design as possible with
secondary data analyses.

00:46:39.225 --> 00:46:40.850
Because we know in
experimental studies

00:46:40.850 --> 00:46:43.430
we can balance confounders
in measured and unmeasured

00:46:43.430 --> 00:46:45.620
because of the
randomization, if it holds,

00:46:45.620 --> 00:46:48.170
but that's not a luxury
in observational research.

00:46:48.170 --> 00:46:50.030
So quasi-experimental
designs, the two

00:46:50.030 --> 00:46:52.280
that I'll talk about
today, can help

00:46:52.280 --> 00:46:54.620
us, if the assumptions
are met and they're

00:46:54.620 --> 00:46:57.500
applied appropriately and
the question is appropriate,

00:46:57.500 --> 00:47:03.610
help us get closer to that
establishing causality.

00:47:03.610 --> 00:47:05.360
So the first analysis
that I'll talk about

00:47:05.360 --> 00:47:08.720
is looking at outcomes of stable
HIV positive patients that

00:47:08.720 --> 00:47:11.930
have been down-referred from a
doctor-managed antiretroviral

00:47:11.930 --> 00:47:14.420
clinic to nurse-managed
primary health care clinic

00:47:14.420 --> 00:47:17.910
for monitoring and treatment
of HIV in South Africa.

00:47:17.910 --> 00:47:19.520
And this is a
prospective cohort study

00:47:19.520 --> 00:47:21.170
where we use propensity
score matching

00:47:21.170 --> 00:47:25.230
to balance confounding between
exposed and the unexposed.

00:47:25.230 --> 00:47:28.810
So we're trying to
simulate clinical trial.

00:47:28.810 --> 00:47:32.369
So here we see that the context
of this is in South Africa.

00:47:32.369 --> 00:47:34.660
And South Africa, just to
give you a bit of background,

00:47:34.660 --> 00:47:36.420
is the largest HIV
epidemic in the world.

00:47:36.420 --> 00:47:40.000
About seven million people
are HIV positive, about 50%

00:47:40.000 --> 00:47:43.850
of those are actually
receiving care for HIV.

00:47:43.850 --> 00:47:49.420
So again, there's a huge unmet
need, but that 50% is not

00:47:49.420 --> 00:47:51.960
a small feat, by any means.

00:47:51.960 --> 00:47:54.990
In the clinic that
the data is from

00:47:54.990 --> 00:47:57.600
and where I've worked
at for about four years

00:47:57.600 --> 00:47:59.640
a while back is
Themba Lethu Clinic,

00:47:59.640 --> 00:48:03.240
which is associated with one of
the largest secondary hospitals

00:48:03.240 --> 00:48:03.930
in Johannesburg.

00:48:03.930 --> 00:48:05.900
It's called Helen
Joseph Hospital.

00:48:05.900 --> 00:48:07.410
And it's central Jo-berg.

00:48:07.410 --> 00:48:11.160
So the population
is a lot of migrants

00:48:11.160 --> 00:48:13.560
back and forth,
Malawi's, Zimbabwean,

00:48:13.560 --> 00:48:18.000
but also a lot of South
African nationals.

00:48:18.000 --> 00:48:21.780
And so what was going on in
this time, roughly around 2007,

00:48:21.780 --> 00:48:25.020
is all of the model of care for
HIV treatment in South Africa

00:48:25.020 --> 00:48:28.300
was doctor-initiated and
then doctor-managed care.

00:48:28.300 --> 00:48:29.700
So they always
felt that HIV care

00:48:29.700 --> 00:48:31.000
had to be managed by doctors.

00:48:31.000 --> 00:48:32.666
They were the only
ones who could do it,

00:48:32.666 --> 00:48:36.040
nurses weren't going to
be capable of doing that.

00:48:36.040 --> 00:48:38.970
But what they started to see
was this overrun clinics, right?

00:48:38.970 --> 00:48:41.067
There were long lines,
patients were leaving,

00:48:41.067 --> 00:48:42.150
getting lost to follow up.

00:48:42.150 --> 00:48:46.000
It was just very difficult to
access care in a timely manner.

00:48:46.000 --> 00:48:49.740
So what they started to do is
de-centralize or down-refer

00:48:49.740 --> 00:48:53.190
patients who were stable to
local primary health care

00:48:53.190 --> 00:48:55.290
clinics that were either
within the vicinity

00:48:55.290 --> 00:48:59.130
of the actual main clinic,
which is Themba Lethu,

00:48:59.130 --> 00:49:01.200
or a primary health
care clinic that was

00:49:01.200 --> 00:49:03.560
closer to the patient's home.

00:49:03.560 --> 00:49:05.810
And so this began in
2007 where Themba Lethu

00:49:05.810 --> 00:49:08.510
began to down-refer their stable
patients to primary health care

00:49:08.510 --> 00:49:09.590
clinics.

00:49:09.590 --> 00:49:11.090
In the primary
health care clinics

00:49:11.090 --> 00:49:16.497
the patients are managed by
nurses, not by doctors, OK?

00:49:16.497 --> 00:49:18.830
So at the same time that this
was going on my colleagues

00:49:18.830 --> 00:49:20.930
were competing what was
called the CIPRA trial.

00:49:20.930 --> 00:49:23.930
It was a non-inferiority
trial comparing nurse

00:49:23.930 --> 00:49:27.410
to doctor-managed
outcomes in patients.

00:49:27.410 --> 00:49:29.900
And what they showed was
nurses can manage patients

00:49:29.900 --> 00:49:31.490
in a clinical trial
setting and have

00:49:31.490 --> 00:49:34.060
comparable outcomes to doctors.

00:49:34.060 --> 00:49:36.680
But what this doesn't
answer is can nurses

00:49:36.680 --> 00:49:38.690
do this in an
observational setting

00:49:38.690 --> 00:49:41.570
where there's not close
supervision or strict inclusion

00:49:41.570 --> 00:49:44.586
criteria of these patients.

00:49:44.586 --> 00:49:46.835
So this is where we went to
the Themba Lethu data set.

00:49:46.835 --> 00:49:48.720
It's a massive database.

00:49:48.720 --> 00:49:50.810
It's a longitudinal
prospective cohort

00:49:50.810 --> 00:49:54.170
and the data is collected
in a database capturing

00:49:54.170 --> 00:49:57.020
system called Therapy Edge
which was designed specifically

00:49:57.020 --> 00:49:59.690
for HIV care and treatment.

00:49:59.690 --> 00:50:01.250
And then at each
clinic we collect

00:50:01.250 --> 00:50:04.580
demographic information,
clinical information, drugs,

00:50:04.580 --> 00:50:06.110
and conditions.

00:50:06.110 --> 00:50:08.210
And currently there's
about 35,000 patients

00:50:08.210 --> 00:50:12.080
that are on treatment
in the database.

00:50:12.080 --> 00:50:14.300
The study population
for this analysis

00:50:14.300 --> 00:50:17.060
was patients who were
adults and initiated

00:50:17.060 --> 00:50:19.310
onto a standard first line
regimen at Themba Lethu

00:50:19.310 --> 00:50:21.860
Clinic after 2004.

00:50:21.860 --> 00:50:24.080
And they had to meet
these eligibility criteria

00:50:24.080 --> 00:50:27.410
for being down-referred to a
primary health care clinic.

00:50:27.410 --> 00:50:29.180
And so that was
stable on treatment,

00:50:29.180 --> 00:50:31.460
they had to have no
opportunistic infections,

00:50:31.460 --> 00:50:34.880
they had to have a higher CD4
count, be virally-suppressed.

00:50:34.880 --> 00:50:36.380
And then the
clinicians, also, there

00:50:36.380 --> 00:50:38.700
were some subjective
measures there

00:50:38.700 --> 00:50:41.330
of whether the clinician felt
they were good candidates

00:50:41.330 --> 00:50:43.190
for down-referral.

00:50:43.190 --> 00:50:47.230
And so in this population,
we were limited once we--

00:50:47.230 --> 00:50:48.730
the eligible patients,
rather, there

00:50:48.730 --> 00:50:50.615
were about 5,000
eligible patients.

00:50:50.615 --> 00:50:52.490
And they were all eligible
for down-referral.

00:50:52.490 --> 00:50:54.570
So they all met these criteria.

00:50:54.570 --> 00:50:59.690
But 1,579 were
actually transferred

00:50:59.690 --> 00:51:01.310
to the primary
health care clinic.

00:51:01.310 --> 00:51:03.740
So we'll consider them
the exposed group.

00:51:03.740 --> 00:51:06.560
And the other
remaining 3,421 were

00:51:06.560 --> 00:51:08.000
eligible but not transferred.

00:51:08.000 --> 00:51:11.730
So we'll refer to them
as the unexposed group.

00:51:11.730 --> 00:51:15.974
And we used logistic regression
to model the propensity

00:51:15.974 --> 00:51:16.890
of receiving exposure.

00:51:16.890 --> 00:51:19.480
And I'll go through this
in a little more detail.

00:51:19.480 --> 00:51:22.260
And then we matched patients
exposed and unexposed

00:51:22.260 --> 00:51:23.980
based on their
propensity score, OK?

00:51:23.980 --> 00:51:27.810
So we're trying to balance
observed and unobserved

00:51:27.810 --> 00:51:30.720
confounders between the
exposed and the unexposed.

00:51:30.720 --> 00:51:32.755
And then we conducted
a survival analysis

00:51:32.755 --> 00:51:33.755
to look at our outcomes.

00:51:35.770 --> 00:51:39.710
So when we're talking about
modeling a patient's propensity

00:51:39.710 --> 00:51:41.560
score, we're looking
at their probability

00:51:41.560 --> 00:51:42.670
of receiving exposure.

00:51:42.670 --> 00:51:44.920
And exposure in
this case is being

00:51:44.920 --> 00:51:46.990
down-referred to the
primary health care clinics.

00:51:46.990 --> 00:51:48.760
Because remember, they're
all eligible for it.

00:51:48.760 --> 00:51:51.093
It's just those that are
down-referred are the ones that

00:51:51.093 --> 00:51:52.540
are actually exposed.

00:51:52.540 --> 00:51:58.120
So we modeled that based on a
set of observed confounders,

00:51:58.120 --> 00:52:01.600
which is gender, age, CD4
count, hemoglobin, body mass

00:52:01.600 --> 00:52:04.410
index, and other factors.

00:52:04.410 --> 00:52:06.740
And so what we have is we
have the entire population.

00:52:06.740 --> 00:52:09.250
The red circle is our
population of patients

00:52:09.250 --> 00:52:12.040
that are down-referred to the
primary health care clinic.

00:52:12.040 --> 00:52:14.590
The blue line is those that
are not down-referred but are

00:52:14.590 --> 00:52:15.760
eligible.

00:52:15.760 --> 00:52:20.680
So we modeled the probability
that the entire population

00:52:20.680 --> 00:52:22.660
would have the exposure
of being transferred

00:52:22.660 --> 00:52:24.550
to the primary
health care clinic.

00:52:24.550 --> 00:52:28.000
And then we matched those
with that overlap of who

00:52:28.000 --> 00:52:31.330
had similar propensity scores.

00:52:31.330 --> 00:52:33.880
And then that matched sample,
that overlapped sample,

00:52:33.880 --> 00:52:35.750
is what we use for our analysis.

00:52:35.750 --> 00:52:38.290
And I'll break that down
in a little more detail.

00:52:38.290 --> 00:52:41.290
But just a basic calculation
of a propensity score.

00:52:41.290 --> 00:52:43.630
So this is a simple
two-by-two table.

00:52:43.630 --> 00:52:45.940
On the left you
have patients that

00:52:45.940 --> 00:52:48.220
have the actual
confounder of interest.

00:52:48.220 --> 00:52:51.070
On the right you have
those that don't have it.

00:52:51.070 --> 00:52:53.950
And then we have simple
exposed and unexposed groups

00:52:53.950 --> 00:52:55.770
within both of those strata.

00:52:55.770 --> 00:52:58.130
You can ignore disease, d
equals one, d equals zero.

00:52:58.130 --> 00:52:59.588
It doesn't even
matter in this case

00:52:59.588 --> 00:53:03.160
because we're just looking
at exposure and confounders.

00:53:03.160 --> 00:53:05.530
So to model someone's
propensity score,

00:53:05.530 --> 00:53:08.560
the probability of receiving--

00:53:08.560 --> 00:53:10.420
probability of
being exposed given

00:53:10.420 --> 00:53:12.940
that you have a
confounder is simply

00:53:12.940 --> 00:53:15.370
84 over the total in the strata.

00:53:15.370 --> 00:53:19.270
Which gives us a
probability of 0.62 or 62%.

00:53:19.270 --> 00:53:21.430
The same thing goes for
the confounder, or those

00:53:21.430 --> 00:53:22.530
without the confounder.

00:53:22.530 --> 00:53:25.030
So if we want to model the
probability of exposure given

00:53:25.030 --> 00:53:26.520
that you don't have
the confounder,

00:53:26.520 --> 00:53:29.980
is simply 177, the
total exposed, divided

00:53:29.980 --> 00:53:31.390
by the total in the strata.

00:53:31.390 --> 00:53:36.460
And that gives us a probability
or propensity of 0.44, 44%.

00:53:36.460 --> 00:53:38.165
So you can think
of in our analysis

00:53:38.165 --> 00:53:41.320
we have person A who's
been down-referred,

00:53:41.320 --> 00:53:44.350
person B who is eligible
for down-referral

00:53:44.350 --> 00:53:45.460
but not down-referred.

00:53:45.460 --> 00:53:47.680
So we have our exposed
and our unexposed.

00:53:47.680 --> 00:53:50.290
And they both have a predicted
probability or propensity

00:53:50.290 --> 00:53:53.500
of 85% of being down-referred.

00:53:53.500 --> 00:53:57.220
So they're identical on
those observe confounders,

00:53:57.220 --> 00:54:00.010
in regards to how we created
our propensity score,

00:54:00.010 --> 00:54:01.690
and their exposure just differs.

00:54:01.690 --> 00:54:04.480
So you can think of them as
essentially randomly assigned,

00:54:04.480 --> 00:54:05.200
OK?

00:54:05.200 --> 00:54:07.019
At least on observed
confounders.

00:54:07.019 --> 00:54:09.310
And I'll keep saying that
because we can't say anything

00:54:09.310 --> 00:54:11.930
about unobserved.

00:54:11.930 --> 00:54:13.770
So this is the actual
data from the study.

00:54:13.770 --> 00:54:17.450
So we had 5,000 patients.

00:54:17.450 --> 00:54:20.000
On the left we had
1,579 which were

00:54:20.000 --> 00:54:21.850
down-referred to the clinic.

00:54:21.850 --> 00:54:24.920
3,421 which were not
down-referred but eligible.

00:54:24.920 --> 00:54:28.640
So on the left is exposed,
on the right is unexposed.

00:54:28.640 --> 00:54:31.910
After getting rid of some
due to exclusion criteria,

00:54:31.910 --> 00:54:35.750
we had a final population
of exposed of 693

00:54:35.750 --> 00:54:40.280
and a final population
of unexposed of 2,968.

00:54:40.280 --> 00:54:41.990
And so we had the
propensity scores

00:54:41.990 --> 00:54:44.010
for that entire population.

00:54:44.010 --> 00:54:49.970
And then we matched the 693
to the 2,968 one to three, OK?

00:54:49.970 --> 00:54:55.970
So we had a final population
of 693 exposed and 2,079

00:54:55.970 --> 00:54:56.700
unexposed.

00:54:56.700 --> 00:54:59.720
So that's our final
analytical population matched

00:54:59.720 --> 00:55:03.306
under propensity to be exposed.

00:55:03.306 --> 00:55:05.180
And this table, this
first table is basically

00:55:05.180 --> 00:55:07.975
what you would see in table
one of a clinical trial, right?

00:55:07.975 --> 00:55:09.350
What we're trying
to show here is

00:55:09.350 --> 00:55:12.200
that we're just balanced
unobserved characteristics

00:55:12.200 --> 00:55:13.772
between exposed and
unexposed groups.

00:55:13.772 --> 00:55:16.230
And you can't probably see it,
the numbers are quite small,

00:55:16.230 --> 00:55:18.540
but you can trust me.

00:55:18.540 --> 00:55:20.510
It is published, so
you can actually check.

00:55:20.510 --> 00:55:22.400
So our exposed group
is down-referred

00:55:22.400 --> 00:55:24.020
and our unexposed
is not down-referred

00:55:24.020 --> 00:55:26.420
and all this shows is that
these characteristics,

00:55:26.420 --> 00:55:29.367
the proportions across
both, are comparable.

00:55:29.367 --> 00:55:30.950
But there's no
significant difference.

00:55:30.950 --> 00:55:33.870
That the propensity
score matching did work

00:55:33.870 --> 00:55:36.060
and it helped us balance
observed confounders

00:55:36.060 --> 00:55:37.050
between the two groups.

00:55:39.989 --> 00:55:42.280
And so what we were able to
conclude with this analysis

00:55:42.280 --> 00:55:44.321
that we couldn't in the
randomized clinical trial

00:55:44.321 --> 00:55:48.070
is that patients managed
by nurses compared

00:55:48.070 --> 00:55:51.805
to patients managed by doctors
for HIV care and treatment

00:55:51.805 --> 00:55:54.430
can have, if not comparable,
if not better outcomes

00:55:54.430 --> 00:55:55.330
in this case.

00:55:55.330 --> 00:55:58.480
Because what we showed, and I
won't go into all the results,

00:55:58.480 --> 00:56:00.730
but what we showed was
that those patients that

00:56:00.730 --> 00:56:05.440
were treated by nurses had an
80% decrease in risk of death,

00:56:05.440 --> 00:56:09.250
70% decrease in risk of loss,
and a 40% decrease in risk

00:56:09.250 --> 00:56:13.060
of viral load rebound or
failure, in this case.

00:56:13.060 --> 00:56:14.287
So they had better outcomes.

00:56:14.287 --> 00:56:16.120
And it's important to
note that the outcomes

00:56:16.120 --> 00:56:18.574
in these-- the events
were quite few in number

00:56:18.574 --> 00:56:19.990
because these are
stable patients.

00:56:19.990 --> 00:56:22.150
So our conclusion
is that the results

00:56:22.150 --> 00:56:24.312
are comparable, if
not maybe better,

00:56:24.312 --> 00:56:26.020
with patients that
are managed by nurses.

00:56:29.150 --> 00:56:33.890
The next analysis here, and this
is from my dissertation work,

00:56:33.890 --> 00:56:37.640
using a regression discontinuity
design to evaluate a policy

00:56:37.640 --> 00:56:39.870
change for HIV in 2010.

00:56:39.870 --> 00:56:43.760
This is an application
of a method

00:56:43.760 --> 00:56:46.880
that I'll continue to use
going forward in my career.

00:56:46.880 --> 00:56:49.460
If it's appropriate, obviously.

00:56:49.460 --> 00:56:52.700
So just a little bit
more background here.

00:56:52.700 --> 00:56:55.837
As I mentioned before,
in 2004 the WHO

00:56:55.837 --> 00:56:57.920
rolled out treatment in
resource limited settings.

00:56:57.920 --> 00:57:00.020
And at that time,
first line therapy

00:57:00.020 --> 00:57:04.340
was two drug classes,
and three drugs total.

00:57:04.340 --> 00:57:06.690
And you don't have to worry
about the fancy names.

00:57:06.690 --> 00:57:09.620
The drugs were two nucleoside
reverse transcriptase

00:57:09.620 --> 00:57:11.930
inhibitors, which was
lamivudine, and then

00:57:11.930 --> 00:57:13.640
stavudine or zidovudine.

00:57:13.640 --> 00:57:15.320
And then one
non-nucleoside reverse

00:57:15.320 --> 00:57:16.730
transcriptase inhibitor.

00:57:16.730 --> 00:57:18.830
And again, the drug
names are not important,

00:57:18.830 --> 00:57:21.410
but you will hear
me say them a lot.

00:57:21.410 --> 00:57:24.710
So stavudine and zidovudine
are the two older drugs

00:57:24.710 --> 00:57:26.960
that were of interest
in this analysis.

00:57:26.960 --> 00:57:29.930
And then in 2010, the WHO
updated their guidelines

00:57:29.930 --> 00:57:33.530
when new drugs became available
in resource limited settings.

00:57:33.530 --> 00:57:36.380
So the drug tenofovir, which
has been used in the high income

00:57:36.380 --> 00:57:39.110
countries since early
2000, finally made its way

00:57:39.110 --> 00:57:40.510
to resource limited settings.

00:57:40.510 --> 00:57:42.800
It was delayed
because of the cost,

00:57:42.800 --> 00:57:45.770
and because one of the main
side effects of tenofovir

00:57:45.770 --> 00:57:47.960
is renal insufficiency
and potentially renal

00:57:47.960 --> 00:57:51.680
failure, which is really
expensive, but rare.

00:57:51.680 --> 00:57:54.620
Also during that time, efficacy
trials were coming out,

00:57:54.620 --> 00:57:57.860
and safety trials, saying that
the side effects of tenofovir

00:57:57.860 --> 00:58:01.250
compared to these older
drugs is a better toxicity

00:58:01.250 --> 00:58:03.170
profile and less side effects.

00:58:03.170 --> 00:58:06.709
So it's a better drug, better
quality of life for patients.

00:58:06.709 --> 00:58:08.250
And then also, the
Clinton Foundation

00:58:08.250 --> 00:58:11.340
did a really good job of
getting the prices down.

00:58:11.340 --> 00:58:13.920
Even though tenofovir is
still four times the cost

00:58:13.920 --> 00:58:16.260
of the older drugs,
it's still much cheaper

00:58:16.260 --> 00:58:20.970
than it was back
in the mid 2000s.

00:58:20.970 --> 00:58:23.220
So what the change
in the WHO guidelines

00:58:23.220 --> 00:58:24.930
set us up to do
here, and this is

00:58:24.930 --> 00:58:28.340
more of the quintessential
quasi-experimental design,

00:58:28.340 --> 00:58:30.150
propensity score.

00:58:30.150 --> 00:58:32.730
There wasn't a cut off, and
there wasn't, obviously,

00:58:32.730 --> 00:58:34.590
any randomization
outside of trying to

00:58:34.590 --> 00:58:36.840
simulate that with
propensity score.

00:58:36.840 --> 00:58:38.700
But this is more of the
quintessential ones.

00:58:38.700 --> 00:58:42.390
What we're doing in this case is
we're not assigning, randomly,

00:58:42.390 --> 00:58:44.740
patients to receive a
treatment or control,

00:58:44.740 --> 00:58:48.950
but they're randomly assigned
based on a policy change.

00:58:48.950 --> 00:58:50.610
And I'll explain
this in more detail,

00:58:50.610 --> 00:58:54.090
but as long as nothing else
is changing, the population

00:58:54.090 --> 00:58:55.590
or outcomes within
that population,

00:58:55.590 --> 00:58:58.170
that policy change is
essentially random.

00:58:58.170 --> 00:59:00.900
And patients on either
side of that policy change

00:59:00.900 --> 00:59:03.660
can be considered similar.

00:59:03.660 --> 00:59:06.878
So we can get what is
called local randomization.

00:59:10.210 --> 00:59:12.910
At that time, there was a
handful of observational work.

00:59:12.910 --> 00:59:15.130
Some of which I had
put out previously,

00:59:15.130 --> 00:59:16.720
myself and my colleagues.

00:59:16.720 --> 00:59:19.224
That was all
prospective cohort work.

00:59:19.224 --> 00:59:20.890
And so what was coming
out was this kind

00:59:20.890 --> 00:59:25.830
of mixed bag of, when comparing
the old drug to the new drug,

00:59:25.830 --> 00:59:26.516
results.

00:59:26.516 --> 00:59:28.390
Some were showing a
higher risk of mortality,

00:59:28.390 --> 00:59:30.056
some were showing a
higher risk of loss,

00:59:30.056 --> 00:59:32.440
some were showing that
they were comparable.

00:59:32.440 --> 00:59:34.450
But we know that in
observational research,

00:59:34.450 --> 00:59:36.430
a lot of this is based
on the assumption

00:59:36.430 --> 00:59:38.410
that when we balance
based, or adjust

00:59:38.410 --> 00:59:41.940
for observed confounders, that
we're balanced on unobserved.

00:59:41.940 --> 00:59:43.930
And that's a strong assumption.

00:59:43.930 --> 00:59:45.820
Also what was
happening at that time

00:59:45.820 --> 00:59:53.560
is two of the studies had
included patients that

00:59:53.560 --> 00:59:55.690
were initiated onto
the new drug prior

00:59:55.690 --> 00:59:57.410
to the change in the policy.

00:59:57.410 --> 00:59:59.560
So these patients had
contraindications,

00:59:59.560 --> 01:00:00.680
or were sicker.

01:00:00.680 --> 01:00:02.950
So they couldn't take the
drugs that were available,

01:00:02.950 --> 01:00:04.930
they could only
take the new drugs.

01:00:04.930 --> 01:00:08.012
This leads to what we refer to
as confounding by indication,

01:00:08.012 --> 01:00:09.970
which is going to cause
them to be at increased

01:00:09.970 --> 01:00:10.890
risk of poor outcomes.

01:00:13.860 --> 01:00:18.200
Regression discontinuity is best
shown visually, at least when

01:00:18.200 --> 01:00:21.690
I learned it, visuals helped.

01:00:21.690 --> 01:00:23.420
So this is a method
that's been used

01:00:23.420 --> 01:00:25.400
in econometrics in
the educational world

01:00:25.400 --> 01:00:26.810
since the 1960s.

01:00:26.810 --> 01:00:28.580
And it's kind of
foreign to epidemiology

01:00:28.580 --> 01:00:31.010
because I think people
get really nervous when

01:00:31.010 --> 01:00:32.540
I don't adjust for anything.

01:00:32.540 --> 01:00:35.480
So there's been some
concern and difficulty

01:00:35.480 --> 01:00:38.910
in getting it published,
but we'll sort that out.

01:00:38.910 --> 01:00:42.650
So what this is
is, in this graph

01:00:42.650 --> 01:00:45.050
we have time on the
horizontal axis.

01:00:45.050 --> 01:00:48.170
And then you have what we will
refer to as the threshold,

01:00:48.170 --> 01:00:48.920
or the cutoff.

01:00:48.920 --> 01:00:50.420
Which in this case,
this dotted line

01:00:50.420 --> 01:00:54.140
represents the date
of policy change.

01:00:54.140 --> 01:00:58.730
And then based on where
in this analysis patients

01:00:58.730 --> 01:01:00.920
will be assigned to
either the control group

01:01:00.920 --> 01:01:02.870
or the experimental
group depending

01:01:02.870 --> 01:01:06.420
on the date of initiation
of treatment for HIV.

01:01:06.420 --> 01:01:08.450
So if a patient
initiates treatment

01:01:08.450 --> 01:01:12.170
prior to the guideline change,
they're in the control group.

01:01:12.170 --> 01:01:14.560
If they initiate treatment
after the guideline change,

01:01:14.560 --> 01:01:16.880
they're in the
experimental group.

01:01:16.880 --> 01:01:20.032
And if there is no
effect of the exposure,

01:01:20.032 --> 01:01:21.740
no effect of that
change in the guideline

01:01:21.740 --> 01:01:23.870
or change in treatment,
then we would expect

01:01:23.870 --> 01:01:25.040
to see something like this.

01:01:25.040 --> 01:01:29.940
No discontinuity or
break at that threshold.

01:01:29.940 --> 01:01:35.970
But if it's the appropriate
method, what we will see

01:01:35.970 --> 01:01:37.740
is this break at the
threshold, and I'll

01:01:37.740 --> 01:01:38.948
show you this in the results.

01:01:38.948 --> 01:01:41.160
So this break at the
threshold is the actual effect

01:01:41.160 --> 01:01:42.520
of the intervention.

01:01:42.520 --> 01:01:46.200
So as long as nothing else is
changing along this timeline,

01:01:46.200 --> 01:01:49.860
outcomes are continuous,
patient demographics

01:01:49.860 --> 01:01:52.050
and clinical characteristics
are the same,

01:01:52.050 --> 01:01:53.940
this is essentially randomized.

01:01:53.940 --> 01:01:55.890
Right around the threshold.

01:01:55.890 --> 01:01:58.792
So we're getting close to
simulating a randomized trial.

01:02:01.740 --> 01:02:04.950
The data source that we
use for this analysis

01:02:04.950 --> 01:02:08.400
is a huge database for
HIV care and treatment.

01:02:08.400 --> 01:02:11.760
It's the International
Epidemiological Database

01:02:11.760 --> 01:02:14.990
for Evaluation of HIV and AIDS.

01:02:14.990 --> 01:02:19.170
It's a NIH funded project where
they pool observational HIV

01:02:19.170 --> 01:02:23.340
databases into regions
all over the world.

01:02:23.340 --> 01:02:26.520
The region that we used for
this was southern Africa.

01:02:26.520 --> 01:02:30.820
Specifically, we used
Zambia in South Africa.

01:02:30.820 --> 01:02:33.670
This analysis is a
prospective cohort study

01:02:33.670 --> 01:02:35.830
where we're applying a
regression discontinuity

01:02:35.830 --> 01:02:37.710
design.

01:02:37.710 --> 01:02:41.055
It's a fairly big
population, over 52,000,

01:02:41.055 --> 01:02:42.930
the majority of which
came from Zambia, where

01:02:42.930 --> 01:02:46.080
there's over 36,000.

01:02:46.080 --> 01:02:49.210
Their HIV positive treatment
naive, non-pregnant, patients

01:02:49.210 --> 01:02:52.040
were greater than
16 years of age.

01:02:52.040 --> 01:02:53.930
Then they had to
initiate treatment

01:02:53.930 --> 01:02:57.320
12 months prior,
or 12 months after,

01:02:57.320 --> 01:02:59.490
the change in the guideline.

01:02:59.490 --> 01:03:03.050
And that date of change
varies between South Africa

01:03:03.050 --> 01:03:03.980
and Zambia.

01:03:03.980 --> 01:03:07.220
South Africa was right along
lines with the World Health

01:03:07.220 --> 01:03:09.920
Organization recommendation,
in April 1, 2010.

01:03:09.920 --> 01:03:13.190
That's when they said change,
and South Africa did that.

01:03:13.190 --> 01:03:15.710
Zambia changed a lot
earlier because they

01:03:15.710 --> 01:03:18.770
got a huge donation from
the pharmaceutical companies

01:03:18.770 --> 01:03:21.800
to roll out tenofovir, the
new drug, at an earlier time.

01:03:21.800 --> 01:03:24.830
So that's why it's
three years earlier.

01:03:24.830 --> 01:03:28.310
But these two dates are the
thresholds, or the cutoff,

01:03:28.310 --> 01:03:30.920
that we used in the analysis.

01:03:30.920 --> 01:03:33.180
Then, all patients had the
potential for 24 months

01:03:33.180 --> 01:03:38.900
of follow up to get a look at
our desired outcomes, which

01:03:38.900 --> 01:03:42.140
were death, attrition, which
is a combination of death

01:03:42.140 --> 01:03:44.510
and loss,
immunological response,

01:03:44.510 --> 01:03:46.670
which is based on
your CD4 change, which

01:03:46.670 --> 01:03:49.640
measures your immune
status, virologic failure,

01:03:49.640 --> 01:03:51.380
and this is HIV failure.

01:03:51.380 --> 01:03:54.770
So two consecutive viral
loads greater than 1,000.

01:03:54.770 --> 01:03:56.630
And then single-drug
substitution, and this

01:03:56.630 --> 01:04:00.380
is an indicator of
toxicity from a drug.

01:04:00.380 --> 01:04:03.110
And we're only looking at
that actual substitution

01:04:03.110 --> 01:04:07.340
within that one class of
stavudine, zidovudine,

01:04:07.340 --> 01:04:08.432
and tenofovir.

01:04:08.432 --> 01:04:09.890
We're not looking
at anything else,

01:04:09.890 --> 01:04:14.300
just seeing if those drugs
are being switched out.

01:04:14.300 --> 01:04:19.410
Coming back to this graph,
regression discontinuity

01:04:19.410 --> 01:04:22.650
can be implemented whenever
exposure is determined

01:04:22.650 --> 01:04:24.290
by the threshold rule.

01:04:24.290 --> 01:04:28.040
So now that data [? verite ?]
initiation is that threshold.

01:04:28.040 --> 01:04:31.460
And I'll refer to what's called
the assignment variable, which

01:04:31.460 --> 01:04:35.210
is going to assign patients to
either side of that threshold.

01:04:35.210 --> 01:04:37.790
And that's the date
they initiate ART.

01:04:37.790 --> 01:04:40.820
So if a patient initiates ART
before the date of guideline

01:04:40.820 --> 01:04:43.700
change, they are
considered in the old drug

01:04:43.700 --> 01:04:45.920
era for the control group.

01:04:45.920 --> 01:04:48.850
If a patient initiates
after the guideline change,

01:04:48.850 --> 01:04:52.250
they're in the new
drug era of tenofovir.

01:04:52.250 --> 01:04:55.850
And then, again, as long as
there is no change in outcomes,

01:04:55.850 --> 01:04:58.950
the patient population
is consistent over time,

01:04:58.950 --> 01:05:01.610
we can assume that
those patients that

01:05:01.610 --> 01:05:03.890
are just above and
below the threshold

01:05:03.890 --> 01:05:06.990
are essentially randomized.

01:05:06.990 --> 01:05:08.520
And we call it
local randomization

01:05:08.520 --> 01:05:11.215
because you can only say
that right around that line.

01:05:11.215 --> 01:05:12.840
The further you go
away from that line,

01:05:12.840 --> 01:05:15.910
the assumption doesn't hold.

01:05:15.910 --> 01:05:18.050
And so they're
essentially random,

01:05:18.050 --> 01:05:20.320
or balanced unobserved
and unobserved factors,

01:05:20.320 --> 01:05:22.736
and the only difference should
be the treatments that they

01:05:22.736 --> 01:05:23.985
receive, is that exposure.

01:05:27.170 --> 01:05:29.109
I'm going to go
through this quickly,

01:05:29.109 --> 01:05:31.400
if you're interested in the
linear regression equation.

01:05:31.400 --> 01:05:33.170
It's a simple linear
regression equation.

01:05:33.170 --> 01:05:35.150
We have a constant.

01:05:35.150 --> 01:05:36.830
We have time and
then interaction

01:05:36.830 --> 01:05:38.450
with the actual treatment.

01:05:38.450 --> 01:05:41.060
We have an exposure indicator.

01:05:41.060 --> 01:05:42.620
And then we have this beta2.

01:05:42.620 --> 01:05:44.420
Within a randomized
clinical trial,

01:05:44.420 --> 01:05:46.580
you're estimating what
we refer to as the intent

01:05:46.580 --> 01:05:47.420
to treat effect.

01:05:47.420 --> 01:05:51.350
So you're analyzing
it based on what

01:05:51.350 --> 01:05:54.930
people were assigned to receive
for treatment or placebo.

01:05:54.930 --> 01:05:57.555
So this beta2 is what
we're interested in.

01:05:57.555 --> 01:05:59.180
We're not controlling
for anything else

01:05:59.180 --> 01:06:00.350
or any other factors
because we're

01:06:00.350 --> 01:06:01.870
assuming that they're balanced.

01:06:01.870 --> 01:06:05.220
And there's ways to check that.

01:06:05.220 --> 01:06:08.310
There is one main threat
to regression discontinuity

01:06:08.310 --> 01:06:10.830
in regards to the
validity of it,

01:06:10.830 --> 01:06:13.710
and that is manipulation
of the assignment variable,

01:06:13.710 --> 01:06:17.260
so that data [? verite ?]
initiation by the individual.

01:06:17.260 --> 01:06:20.760
And you can think of potentially
two different scenarios, which

01:06:20.760 --> 01:06:23.460
I think are highly unlikely,
but you could see happening.

01:06:23.460 --> 01:06:27.750
Where a patient knows that
there is a new drug coming out

01:06:27.750 --> 01:06:30.480
after a certain date,
and so they hold off

01:06:30.480 --> 01:06:33.030
on going into the clinic to
initiate care until that drug

01:06:33.030 --> 01:06:34.522
is available.

01:06:34.522 --> 01:06:35.480
That's highly unlikely.

01:06:35.480 --> 01:06:37.970
Patients aren't really
in tune to what's

01:06:37.970 --> 01:06:40.670
going on at a national level
and what the policies are.

01:06:40.670 --> 01:06:42.590
So that's most likely unlikely.

01:06:42.590 --> 01:06:45.500
You could also see a scenario
where a clinician could delay

01:06:45.500 --> 01:06:47.420
treatment because they
know this new drug is

01:06:47.420 --> 01:06:48.710
going to be available.

01:06:48.710 --> 01:06:49.850
But that's unethical.

01:06:49.850 --> 01:06:52.910
These patients are coming into
the treatment extremely sick,

01:06:52.910 --> 01:06:54.600
their CD4 count
is very, very low.

01:06:54.600 --> 01:06:57.360
So to send them away
without drugs is unethical.

01:06:57.360 --> 01:07:00.200
So that could be occurring,
but we don't believe it is,

01:07:00.200 --> 01:07:02.940
and there's ways
to test for that.

01:07:02.940 --> 01:07:06.634
We can test for that by looking
at if our observed confounders

01:07:06.634 --> 01:07:08.550
are balanced on either
side of the thresholds.

01:07:08.550 --> 01:07:11.510
So is our patient
population consistent?

01:07:11.510 --> 01:07:14.314
And then we can also see if
there's that manipulation,

01:07:14.314 --> 01:07:16.730
if people are delaying treatment
until after the guideline

01:07:16.730 --> 01:07:19.070
change, by just
basically graphing

01:07:19.070 --> 01:07:21.830
the numbers of initiates
bend in weekly intervals

01:07:21.830 --> 01:07:23.450
in our time period
to see if there's

01:07:23.450 --> 01:07:25.520
any, what we refer
to as bunching,

01:07:25.520 --> 01:07:29.010
on the right side
of the threshold.

01:07:29.010 --> 01:07:30.620
So the results.

01:07:30.620 --> 01:07:33.830
This is basically a table 1 in
a randomized clinical trial.

01:07:33.830 --> 01:07:36.860
And all it's showing you is
we have South Africa here,

01:07:36.860 --> 01:07:38.960
we have Zambia here.

01:07:38.960 --> 01:07:40.692
We have our observed
confounders here,

01:07:40.692 --> 01:07:42.650
which the only things we
could actually measure

01:07:42.650 --> 01:07:45.590
were age, gender, CD4 count,
weight and hemoglobin.

01:07:45.590 --> 01:07:47.840
These are all clinical and
demographic characteristics

01:07:47.840 --> 01:07:49.520
of patients.

01:07:49.520 --> 01:07:53.510
What we saw, there was
no significant difference

01:07:53.510 --> 01:07:55.520
between our exposed and
our unexposed group,

01:07:55.520 --> 01:07:58.460
or a treatment and control on
either side of the threshold.

01:07:58.460 --> 01:08:01.310
On either side of that
line, they were similar

01:08:01.310 --> 01:08:04.870
in South Africa and in Zambia.

01:08:04.870 --> 01:08:08.047
And that's all that's showing.

01:08:08.047 --> 01:08:10.630
To see if there was any of that
manipulation of the assignment

01:08:10.630 --> 01:08:12.296
variable, people were
delaying treatment

01:08:12.296 --> 01:08:14.704
until after the guidelines
actually happened,

01:08:14.704 --> 01:08:16.120
this is just the
graph where we're

01:08:16.120 --> 01:08:19.420
looking at the number
of patients initiating.

01:08:19.420 --> 01:08:21.100
So we have the red
line-- and this

01:08:21.100 --> 01:08:23.319
is for the other graphs
I'll show you-- is always

01:08:23.319 --> 01:08:27.040
the threshold or the cutoff
in Zambia and in South Africa.

01:08:27.040 --> 01:08:29.080
And then patients,
again, are initiated

01:08:29.080 --> 01:08:31.630
on either side of this threshold
and either on the control

01:08:31.630 --> 01:08:34.240
group, or the treatment group.

01:08:34.240 --> 01:08:37.750
Then we have just number
of initiates on the y-axis.

01:08:37.750 --> 01:08:40.240
Then time on the x-axis,
so 12 months on this side,

01:08:40.240 --> 01:08:42.399
and 12 months on this side.

01:08:42.399 --> 01:08:44.950
These black arrows
represent seasonal trends

01:08:44.950 --> 01:08:46.779
in South Africa, so
we expect to see dips

01:08:46.779 --> 01:08:50.350
in patients, the numbers
initiating treatment.

01:08:50.350 --> 01:08:53.979
What we're looking at here
is, if those patients who

01:08:53.979 --> 01:08:57.640
could have initiated over here
were delaying for some reason,

01:08:57.640 --> 01:09:00.430
we would expect to see this
huge increase in patient numbers

01:09:00.430 --> 01:09:02.214
on the right side
of that red line,

01:09:02.214 --> 01:09:04.630
because they were manipulating
the date that they actually

01:09:04.630 --> 01:09:06.131
initiated treatment.

01:09:06.131 --> 01:09:06.880
We don't see that.

01:09:06.880 --> 01:09:09.850
We see a slight dip in
South Africa and in Zambia,

01:09:09.850 --> 01:09:12.020
but then the numbers
basically increase

01:09:12.020 --> 01:09:15.399
to the numbers that were
previously there, or previously

01:09:15.399 --> 01:09:16.391
being initiated.

01:09:16.391 --> 01:09:18.640
So we don't feel like there's
evidence of manipulation

01:09:18.640 --> 01:09:22.040
of the assignment variable.

01:09:22.040 --> 01:09:25.819
This figure is just showing
the actual probability

01:09:25.819 --> 01:09:26.660
of tenofovir.

01:09:26.660 --> 01:09:28.729
So again, to orient
you, red line

01:09:28.729 --> 01:09:30.359
is the date of the
guideline change,

01:09:30.359 --> 01:09:33.200
and then control or
treatment on either side.

01:09:33.200 --> 01:09:35.180
And this is just the
proportion of patients

01:09:35.180 --> 01:09:36.629
that are initiating tenofovir.

01:09:36.629 --> 01:09:39.170
This is the reason that we felt
like regression discontinuity

01:09:39.170 --> 01:09:42.700
was a good design option,
because you can see right

01:09:42.700 --> 01:09:46.250
at this threshold, the
exposure substantially

01:09:46.250 --> 01:09:47.720
increases in South Africa.

01:09:47.720 --> 01:09:51.040
We go 81%, a risk
difference of 81%.

01:09:51.040 --> 01:09:53.300
And a risk difference
of 41% in Zambia.

01:09:53.300 --> 01:09:56.270
And remember, they delayed,
and it wasn't nationally done,

01:09:56.270 --> 01:10:00.710
so Zambia didn't have
as stark of a contrast.

01:10:00.710 --> 01:10:01.377
So that's great.

01:10:01.377 --> 01:10:03.626
That's where we're like, OK,
regression discontinuity.

01:10:03.626 --> 01:10:05.410
There is a discontinuity
in our exposure

01:10:05.410 --> 01:10:11.290
at that policy change, which we
were very excited about that.

01:10:11.290 --> 01:10:12.790
This was the only
outcome that there

01:10:12.790 --> 01:10:14.145
was a significant difference.

01:10:14.145 --> 01:10:15.520
The orientation's
the same, we're

01:10:15.520 --> 01:10:17.920
looking at the proportion
of single-drug substitution

01:10:17.920 --> 01:10:21.150
on the y-axis,
and time on the x.

01:10:21.150 --> 01:10:22.780
South Africa and Zambia.

01:10:22.780 --> 01:10:24.280
And single-drug
substitution is just

01:10:24.280 --> 01:10:26.560
that indicator of toxicity.

01:10:26.560 --> 01:10:30.220
So we see a significant
decrease in toxicity, a risk

01:10:30.220 --> 01:10:32.350
difference of negative 15.

01:10:32.350 --> 01:10:34.780
And then a risk difference
of a decrease of negative two

01:10:34.780 --> 01:10:35.280
in Zambia.

01:10:35.280 --> 01:10:37.870
So not as large, but still
a significant decrease.

01:10:37.870 --> 01:10:41.410
And this was expected
since tenofovir

01:10:41.410 --> 01:10:43.000
has a better side
effect and toxicity

01:10:43.000 --> 01:10:46.345
profile from the other drugs.

01:10:46.345 --> 01:10:48.720
Then these other graphs, this
is just South Africa alone.

01:10:48.720 --> 01:10:50.499
These are the other outcomes.

01:10:50.499 --> 01:10:52.790
And remember how I said if
we had expected that there'd

01:10:52.790 --> 01:10:54.840
be no effective
exposure on the outcome,

01:10:54.840 --> 01:10:57.180
we would just see a flat line.

01:10:57.180 --> 01:11:01.890
There was really no effect on
any of these other outcomes.

01:11:01.890 --> 01:11:04.282
We have death, attrition,
mean CD4 count,

01:11:04.282 --> 01:11:05.240
and viral load failure.

01:11:05.240 --> 01:11:07.080
So there really was
not a difference.

01:11:07.080 --> 01:11:09.150
The exposure did not
affect the outcome.

01:11:09.150 --> 01:11:10.390
Which should be.

01:11:10.390 --> 01:11:11.880
These drugs are
comparable, they're

01:11:11.880 --> 01:11:16.070
effective at treating
HIV if they're taken.

01:11:16.070 --> 01:11:17.160
Then this is just Zambia.

01:11:17.160 --> 01:11:19.530
And we see again, we didn't
look at viral load failure,

01:11:19.530 --> 01:11:22.550
but you see death, loss,
and then CD4 count.

01:11:22.550 --> 01:11:23.910
They're flat.

01:11:23.910 --> 01:11:27.960
So the policy change, or
that exposure to tenofovir,

01:11:27.960 --> 01:11:29.580
didn't have a
significant increase

01:11:29.580 --> 01:11:32.850
or decrease in the
outcomes in this case.

01:11:32.850 --> 01:11:39.230
In summary, the study
allowed us to say

01:11:39.230 --> 01:11:42.339
that starting patients on
tenofovir standard of care

01:11:42.339 --> 01:11:43.880
reduced single-drug
substitutions, so

01:11:43.880 --> 01:11:45.530
reduced toxicity.

01:11:45.530 --> 01:11:47.960
But there were no changes
in other observed outcomes,

01:11:47.960 --> 01:11:50.800
in this case.

01:11:50.800 --> 01:11:52.430
Strengths were huge
sample size, you'd

01:11:52.430 --> 01:11:54.430
be hard-pressed to get
this in a clinical trial.

01:11:54.430 --> 01:11:55.600
It'd be very expensive
and you would

01:11:55.600 --> 01:11:57.970
spend your whole entire life,
and your children's life,

01:11:57.970 --> 01:11:58.761
trying to get that.

01:12:01.270 --> 01:12:04.056
If the assumptions are met
in a regression discontinuity

01:12:04.056 --> 01:12:05.930
design, it's less
vulnerable to major threats

01:12:05.930 --> 01:12:08.050
to validity, like a lot
of observational research

01:12:08.050 --> 01:12:10.970
that we do is, because
of the assumptions.

01:12:10.970 --> 01:12:13.360
We can check those
threats to validity

01:12:13.360 --> 01:12:16.480
by looking at if our observed
confounders are balanced,

01:12:16.480 --> 01:12:19.510
or if there's any manipulation
of the assignment variable.

01:12:19.510 --> 01:12:22.240
And we saw that there was none.

01:12:22.240 --> 01:12:25.240
Hopefully what I've shown
you by these two examples

01:12:25.240 --> 01:12:28.390
is that, as we move
from these descriptive

01:12:28.390 --> 01:12:31.660
studies in observational
world into analytical, down

01:12:31.660 --> 01:12:36.150
towards the randomized clinical
trial, our gold standard,

01:12:36.150 --> 01:12:39.550
quasi experimental designs can
help us, if applied properly

01:12:39.550 --> 01:12:42.400
and the assumptions are met,
to get a little bit closer

01:12:42.400 --> 01:12:44.086
to that establishing causality.

01:12:44.086 --> 01:12:45.460
So instead of
correlation, we can

01:12:45.460 --> 01:12:48.790
say that an exposure actually
causes the outcome that

01:12:48.790 --> 01:12:51.496
were of interest.

01:12:51.496 --> 01:12:52.474
Thank you.

01:12:52.474 --> 01:12:58.831
[APPLAUSE]

01:12:58.831 --> 01:13:00.298
- That was absolutely
fascinating.

01:13:00.298 --> 01:13:01.390
Thank you.

01:13:01.390 --> 01:13:07.615
And now we have 15 or 20
minutes for your questions.

01:13:07.615 --> 01:13:09.490
And while you are thinking
of your questions,

01:13:09.490 --> 01:13:11.440
maybe I'll ask one
or two of mine.

01:13:14.100 --> 01:13:18.580
Neal, I was struck
by the slide up there

01:13:18.580 --> 01:13:23.890
that showed the proportion
of patient contacts

01:13:23.890 --> 01:13:26.920
by what the procedure was.

01:13:26.920 --> 01:13:30.460
Checking vital signs was right
there at the top, like 36%,

01:13:30.460 --> 01:13:33.850
38%, something like that.

01:13:33.850 --> 01:13:38.900
As you think about the
propensity for those contacts

01:13:38.900 --> 01:13:43.640
in that network to
cause infection,

01:13:43.640 --> 01:13:47.960
do you think about changing the
frequency of those procedures?

01:13:47.960 --> 01:13:50.240
Is there any talk
about, maybe you

01:13:50.240 --> 01:13:53.480
don't need to take vital
signs quite as often?

01:13:53.480 --> 01:13:56.510
I'm sort of wondering how you
think about the procedures

01:13:56.510 --> 01:13:57.920
in that mix.

01:13:57.920 --> 01:14:01.550
- So the procedures
themselves, we actually

01:14:01.550 --> 01:14:04.070
ranked the procedures
based on propensity

01:14:04.070 --> 01:14:05.460
to spread in organisms.

01:14:05.460 --> 01:14:08.420
So something like
vital signs, it

01:14:08.420 --> 01:14:11.990
was like the lowest threshold
that's possible that we thought

01:14:11.990 --> 01:14:13.766
could actually spread MRSA.

01:14:13.766 --> 01:14:15.140
But some of the
other procedures,

01:14:15.140 --> 01:14:18.110
like the stool description and
testing procedure that I think

01:14:18.110 --> 01:14:20.690
was the second or third
most common, yeah.

01:14:20.690 --> 01:14:23.910
I think that does warrant
reviewing that policy

01:14:23.910 --> 01:14:26.330
to say, why are we
doing this so much?

01:14:26.330 --> 01:14:28.860
Unless there's a good
reason for doing it,

01:14:28.860 --> 01:14:32.840
this is a clear opportunity
for MRSA transmission to occur.

01:14:32.840 --> 01:14:36.140
Even though it's done
under non-sterile gloving,

01:14:36.140 --> 01:14:40.040
there still is the potential
for something to happen.

01:14:40.040 --> 01:14:43.920
These are the kinds of
conversations that, this works,

01:14:43.920 --> 01:14:47.600
spawned with our infection
control group at the hospital.

01:14:47.600 --> 01:14:50.990
And actually, I
hadn't particularly

01:14:50.990 --> 01:14:53.409
thought of that, so I want
to go back right now and--

01:14:53.409 --> 01:14:54.200
- Excellent, great.

01:14:54.200 --> 01:14:56.720
- --say, how often are we
actually doing these things?

01:14:56.720 --> 01:14:59.070
And do we need to
do them as often?

01:14:59.070 --> 01:14:59.695
- Yeah.

01:14:59.695 --> 01:15:03.590
A really, really
interesting analysis.

01:15:03.590 --> 01:15:09.840
Thinking also about acuity, and
the increased risk of acuity,

01:15:09.840 --> 01:15:13.310
which is that mix of severity
of the cases in your NICU.

01:15:13.310 --> 01:15:16.310
Is that an individual
characteristic,

01:15:16.310 --> 01:15:19.814
or is that also as a
proportion of your population.

01:15:19.814 --> 01:15:21.980
It's sort of interesting
to think about the tension.

01:15:21.980 --> 01:15:23.780
Like when the acuity
is high, is it

01:15:23.780 --> 01:15:26.700
the highly acute
cases who get sick,

01:15:26.700 --> 01:15:29.070
or is it everybody's
risk that increases?

01:15:29.070 --> 01:15:30.290
- Yes it's both.

01:15:30.290 --> 01:15:30.860
It's both.

01:15:30.860 --> 01:15:33.080
It's the highly acute
patients because they

01:15:33.080 --> 01:15:34.282
are at the greater risk.

01:15:34.282 --> 01:15:36.365
They're having more done
to them and they're sick,

01:15:36.365 --> 01:15:39.080
or they may have a less of
a developed immune system

01:15:39.080 --> 01:15:40.220
and skin system.

01:15:40.220 --> 01:15:41.720
But then it's that
breakdown that

01:15:41.720 --> 01:15:46.840
happens overall, especially
if there's a code in the unit.

01:15:46.840 --> 01:15:49.130
If there's a code in the
unit, then all the demands

01:15:49.130 --> 01:15:53.066
get focused right away on
that very critical infant.

01:15:53.066 --> 01:15:54.440
And then you have
to think about,

01:15:54.440 --> 01:15:56.510
as the groups
disperse from the code

01:15:56.510 --> 01:15:59.180
to go back to caring with
the other, at that moment,

01:15:59.180 --> 01:16:02.710
they are most vulnerable
to spreading something

01:16:02.710 --> 01:16:04.310
if that particular
patient happened

01:16:04.310 --> 01:16:07.346
to have been
colonized or infected.

01:16:07.346 --> 01:16:08.690
- Really Interesting.

01:16:08.690 --> 01:16:13.100
So Alana, I think the
regression discontinuity

01:16:13.100 --> 01:16:14.480
is really interesting.

01:16:14.480 --> 01:16:18.690
And I'm thinking of
other opportunities

01:16:18.690 --> 01:16:22.200
for doing that, and also
thinking about sometimes

01:16:22.200 --> 01:16:25.770
we get natural experiments
or disasters that

01:16:25.770 --> 01:16:29.970
afford the same kind of
opportunity or threshold

01:16:29.970 --> 01:16:31.970
as a policy change.

01:16:31.970 --> 01:16:34.680
We once did a
study where we were

01:16:34.680 --> 01:16:39.810
looking at the risk of preterm
delivery in a pregnancy cohort

01:16:39.810 --> 01:16:42.390
that we had going
on here in Boston.

01:16:42.390 --> 01:16:46.680
And we were interested in
the role of acute stressors.

01:16:46.680 --> 01:16:51.060
And September 11 happened right
in the middle of that cohort,

01:16:51.060 --> 01:16:55.019
so we were able to look
on either side of it.

01:16:55.019 --> 01:16:57.060
But one of the things I
remember we wrestled with

01:16:57.060 --> 01:17:02.670
is how much time is
eligible before the event,

01:17:02.670 --> 01:17:04.000
and then after the event.

01:17:04.000 --> 01:17:06.330
And does that need to
be comparable length,

01:17:06.330 --> 01:17:10.461
and how do you define
that against the risk of--

01:17:10.461 --> 01:17:11.960
the risk to these
things, of course,

01:17:11.960 --> 01:17:15.440
is there's perhaps a
secular change going on

01:17:15.440 --> 01:17:16.880
in the background.

01:17:16.880 --> 01:17:18.680
I wondered if you'd
talk about that.

01:17:18.680 --> 01:17:20.870
- So in this
analysis, you can have

01:17:20.870 --> 01:17:24.840
a window around the
threshold if you want.

01:17:24.840 --> 01:17:26.582
Something like, I
mean there's obviously

01:17:26.582 --> 01:17:28.040
a date with September
11, but there

01:17:28.040 --> 01:17:29.600
could be some
window around that,

01:17:29.600 --> 01:17:32.960
where it could help you kind
of tease out the discontinuity

01:17:32.960 --> 01:17:33.872
more clearly.

01:17:33.872 --> 01:17:34.580
But you're right.

01:17:34.580 --> 01:17:37.940
With something like a natural
disaster or a terrorist attack,

01:17:37.940 --> 01:17:41.630
there are other
underlying factors

01:17:41.630 --> 01:17:43.100
that may not be consistent.

01:17:43.100 --> 01:17:46.310
Where that local randomization
or continuous outcomes

01:17:46.310 --> 01:17:50.940
assumptions that
you have to make

01:17:50.940 --> 01:17:54.480
would be actually consistent,
those assumptions would be met,

01:17:54.480 --> 01:17:57.525
is what I would be a
bit concerned about.

01:17:57.525 --> 01:17:59.400
Just because of everything
that also could be

01:17:59.400 --> 01:18:02.290
changing around that time date.

01:18:02.290 --> 01:18:04.290
We're using this going forward.

01:18:04.290 --> 01:18:07.470
In South Africa, we're building
a national level cohort

01:18:07.470 --> 01:18:12.000
of HIV, and then also with
chronic diseases, diabetes

01:18:12.000 --> 01:18:16.040
and cardiovascular disease, by
doing a lot more big data work.

01:18:16.040 --> 01:18:18.840
We're using a laboratory system
that they have in South Africa

01:18:18.840 --> 01:18:22.830
to link labs to each other to
create individuals and create

01:18:22.830 --> 01:18:26.670
prospective cohorts and then
assess policy changes over time

01:18:26.670 --> 01:18:29.220
where it's like a
clear cut policy,

01:18:29.220 --> 01:18:31.140
and there isn't this kind of--

01:18:31.140 --> 01:18:33.030
I think a natural
disaster or anything

01:18:33.030 --> 01:18:36.370
around that may be a little
bit more difficult to make

01:18:36.370 --> 01:18:38.190
sure the assumptions are met.

01:18:38.190 --> 01:18:41.940
But it'd be interesting to try.

01:18:41.940 --> 01:18:43.575
- Let's open up to questions.

01:18:49.020 --> 01:18:51.140
- I'm a particle
physicist, so I come

01:18:51.140 --> 01:18:55.640
from a complete different
domain of how we do analysis.

01:18:55.640 --> 01:18:57.560
One of the things
I was curious about

01:18:57.560 --> 01:19:00.050
is, we have this set of
tools called Monte Carlos.

01:19:00.050 --> 01:19:04.130
And basically, we take a model
of the system we're studying,

01:19:04.130 --> 01:19:09.950
including random stuff,
diffusion, that sort of thing.

01:19:09.950 --> 01:19:13.550
It just struck me that when
you try to do a validation,

01:19:13.550 --> 01:19:15.200
the nice thing
about Monte Carlo is

01:19:15.200 --> 01:19:21.770
that you can run 100 times what
you just did for the HIV study,

01:19:21.770 --> 01:19:24.590
or 100 times what you
just did, and then you

01:19:24.590 --> 01:19:26.660
can judge the
statistical significance

01:19:26.660 --> 01:19:31.220
rather than just using the
more refined statistical tools.

01:19:31.220 --> 01:19:33.200
I was wondering if
there's any attempt

01:19:33.200 --> 01:19:36.810
to move towards
that in the field

01:19:36.810 --> 01:19:39.810
that you're using these
secondary sources?

01:19:42.311 --> 01:19:42.810
- Yes.

01:19:42.810 --> 01:19:44.309
In fact, I have
many colleagues that

01:19:44.309 --> 01:19:48.840
would be quite encouraged
by your comment there.

01:19:48.840 --> 01:19:50.280
Some of the other
work that I do,

01:19:50.280 --> 01:19:52.650
I use a lot of
Bayesian methods, where

01:19:52.650 --> 01:19:55.002
we bring in prior information.

01:19:55.002 --> 01:19:57.210
We don't start out assuming
everyone's at equal risk.

01:19:57.210 --> 01:19:59.830
We assume some groups are
at greater risk than others,

01:19:59.830 --> 01:20:02.010
and then we run these
simulations, many hundreds

01:20:02.010 --> 01:20:03.100
of thousands of times.

01:20:03.100 --> 01:20:06.450
So there's definitely a movement
of foot in the field to go more

01:20:06.450 --> 01:20:08.130
towards that direction.

01:20:08.130 --> 01:20:12.120
But from a teaching
aspect, it's still

01:20:12.120 --> 01:20:16.050
being taught in a
traditional framework.

01:20:16.050 --> 01:20:17.890
Just like, here's
how to get started.

01:20:17.890 --> 01:20:22.380
So in some sense, it
has its own momentum

01:20:22.380 --> 01:20:24.780
and it's being taught this way.

01:20:24.780 --> 01:20:27.390
But there are more and more
people using the techniques

01:20:27.390 --> 01:20:29.250
that you're describing.

01:20:29.250 --> 01:20:31.560
- And I think as myself
and my colleagues

01:20:31.560 --> 01:20:33.450
move into more of the
big data world, which

01:20:33.450 --> 01:20:36.960
is kind of a broad term, a
lot of those techniques we're

01:20:36.960 --> 01:20:38.850
talking about applying.

01:20:38.850 --> 01:20:40.380
So yes, there's movement.

01:20:40.380 --> 01:20:43.650
But you're right, it's taught
more in a traditional sense.

01:20:43.650 --> 01:20:46.730
- I don't know if I'm
speaking for you as well.

01:20:46.730 --> 01:20:48.600
Our field, I feel,
uses a lot of methods

01:20:48.600 --> 01:20:52.170
that come from other places.

01:20:52.170 --> 01:20:57.170
For example, social sciences.

01:20:57.170 --> 01:20:59.820
The methods that I'm
using for the work

01:20:59.820 --> 01:21:02.100
that I presented on multilevel
analysis, a lot of that

01:21:02.100 --> 01:21:04.090
comes from the social sciences.

01:21:04.090 --> 01:21:06.240
So I feel that your
group is pioneering

01:21:06.240 --> 01:21:08.680
some of these methods, and
speaks well for our group

01:21:08.680 --> 01:21:11.179
and it'll just take a little
bit of time to catch up to you.

01:21:13.422 --> 01:21:14.868
- Other questions?

01:21:21.630 --> 01:21:22.160
- Hi.

01:21:22.160 --> 01:21:25.470
It's a question for Neal.

01:21:25.470 --> 01:21:30.030
How much variation are there
in NICUs in other places?

01:21:30.030 --> 01:21:31.960
Is there a, kind
of, gold standard

01:21:31.960 --> 01:21:35.560
where they don't have
these problems at all?

01:21:35.560 --> 01:21:38.490
- Absolutely, critical
care management of babies

01:21:38.490 --> 01:21:40.510
differs institution
to institution.

01:21:40.510 --> 01:21:43.410
So in some sense,
I wonder with you,

01:21:43.410 --> 01:21:48.600
how generalizable are our
findings to other NICUs.

01:21:48.600 --> 01:21:52.440
A lot of the day to day
what goes on in NICU

01:21:52.440 --> 01:21:55.500
is fairly well prescribed,
and they follow

01:21:55.500 --> 01:21:57.220
protocols and guidelines.

01:21:57.220 --> 01:22:00.450
So in some sense, there
will be a variation.

01:22:00.450 --> 01:22:02.940
I would love to actually
repeat this analysis

01:22:02.940 --> 01:22:06.000
with a whole group of NICUs
and see what's out there.

01:22:06.000 --> 01:22:11.580
But if another NICU is
doing some infection control

01:22:11.580 --> 01:22:14.580
procedure because they
have a flag in their EMR

01:22:14.580 --> 01:22:19.200
to say it's a high census right
now or it's a high unit acuity,

01:22:19.200 --> 01:22:22.380
then our findings may not
necessarily apply to them.

01:22:22.380 --> 01:22:24.260
That is kind of a
next step, I think,

01:22:24.260 --> 01:22:26.340
with this work is
let's see if we can

01:22:26.340 --> 01:22:28.070
replicate this in other NICUs.

01:22:28.070 --> 01:22:31.020
Is this something just
specific to Christiana care,

01:22:31.020 --> 01:22:34.020
or is this truly a
generalizable issue that's

01:22:34.020 --> 01:22:35.220
happening across the board.

01:22:40.870 --> 01:22:43.930
- As a follow up
question, the size

01:22:43.930 --> 01:22:50.320
of the NICU that you described
is considerably larger

01:22:50.320 --> 01:22:53.150
than the community hospitals
that I've worked at.

01:22:53.150 --> 01:22:58.150
It would be interesting to
compare the size of the NICU

01:22:58.150 --> 01:23:01.150
in terms of the outcomes,
because this would certainly

01:23:01.150 --> 01:23:04.870
have a significant
effect on advice as

01:23:04.870 --> 01:23:07.850
to whether regionalize
this kind of care

01:23:07.850 --> 01:23:11.350
or whether it can be as
diffusive as it is now.

01:23:11.350 --> 01:23:12.340
- Yes.

01:23:12.340 --> 01:23:16.390
I'm dealing with a level 3 NICU
that can go up to 70 patients.

01:23:16.390 --> 01:23:20.470
And if you consider a smaller
regional hospital that

01:23:20.470 --> 01:23:25.786
maybe has like a 10 or even just
a very, very small 5 bed NICU,

01:23:25.786 --> 01:23:29.791
I think that's a great
question to explore.

01:23:29.791 --> 01:23:30.290
- All right.

